<HEAD>Nixon Planning China Trip: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, who reopened ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the 1970s, is planning to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in September, according to a published report. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials and diplomatic sources were quoted in Saturday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> as saying that <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> were likely to be among the first prominent Americans to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators last month <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> did not respond to inquiries about his <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plans, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>, who served under <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and helped forge relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, was quoted as saying he was considering a `` long-standing invitation'' to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in October to take part in a government-sponsored investment conference. `` I wo n't conduct foreign policy on my own,'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> said. `` I would n't do anything without consulting the administration.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has barred high-level official trips to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a sign of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> displeasure with the massacre in Tiananmen Square. The order extends only to executive branch officials. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in February 1972 re-established Sino-American relations for the first time since the 1949 communist revolution. He has made three other trips to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> has expressed disapproval of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions, saying that messages should be sent through private channels asking the Chinese to show restraint.
