<HEAD>Officials Appealed To Panamanian Government In Exile For Drug Bust</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 11-13 bgng: `In Panama,'' with reaction in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration appealed to a powerless government in exile for permission to board a Panamanian freighter off Key West and was readily accommodated, leading to the seizure of 3,359 pounds of cocaine, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> explained Friday. `` Can you tell us which government gave the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> permission, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s or the Panamanian government we recognize in exile?'' a reporter asked during the daily <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> briefing. `` The Department of State requested permission from the <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> government through the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and Ambassador <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and permission was granted,'' spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> responded. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recognizes <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as the legitimate president of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> was ousted from the office in February 1988 at the urging of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto ruler, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, indicted by a grand jury in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, also overturned the results of the May 7 election, which showed an opposition candidate as the winner. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> was not a candidate. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> responded to the election fraud by sending in American troops to bolster the 10,000 or so soldiers already there, withdrawing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador and cutting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy staff. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> boarded the Panamanian freighter Thursday night and found the hidden sacks of cocaine. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> put the street value of the drugs at $ 129.5 million. Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> boarded the 162-foot captured freighter at <LOCATION> Key </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> on Friday and praised the interception, saying: `` What this means is that we have begun to coerce the smuggler back out on the sea, and out of the air.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the ship's position, off the direct route to the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, aroused suspicion. But an initial search of ship failed to turn up anything, officials said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> went to the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and we were given approval to go ahead and board the ship,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Karonis </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, government authorities said Friday they were satisfied that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> had captured a drug-running vessel but were upset that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had gotten permission from the <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> government. `` We are very happy that the Americans have made this capture,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrera </PERSON> of the prosecutor's office. He added, `` We are annoyed about the manner'' that they sought permission. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> have had an anti-drug agreement since 1976 which mandates cooperation from both sides. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a reporter at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> briefing pressed the issue: `` Is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' view that the <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> government in exile has the authority to grant permission for interception of a ship? Is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' view that the <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> government in exile has the authority to grant permission for any sort of military or paramilitary activity such as the use of <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> forces to stop shipping to and from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said: `` If we decide we're going to try to board the vessel, we go to the government and get permission. We certainly do recognize the <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> government as the government of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and we recognize, therefore, that they have the authority to give us permission, and then we board the vessel.''
