<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Elections,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Upheaval Shakes '89 Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Abortion advocates have staked out <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> for the first true test of their punch at the polls, saying they'll hit the hustings and slug it out on the airwaves in an all-out effort to elect a pro-choice Democrat as governor. `` Abortion is going to be smack dab in the middle of this election,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowker </PERSON>, state chief of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>. With so few political races this year, `` we are going to be the target state,'' she said. This week's upheaval in abortion law has jarred other 1989 campaigns, particularly the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> gubernatorial and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> mayoral elections. But it is in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> that the issue has risen quickly to the political fore. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s race, like <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s, pits an anti-abortion Republican against a pro-choice Democrat. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, pro-choice Democratic Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> is attacking the neutral stand of Republican <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>. `` People who believe in a woman's right to abortion ... ought to be fearful of <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> has said. A <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> aide on Wednesday accused the mayor of fearmongering. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> began his attacks on the issue months ago, but abortion gained new prominence as a political issue Monday, when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> approved of greater abortion restrictions by the states. Pro-choice groups promptly pledged to fight new anti-abortion laws and to work for the election of candidates who favor legal abortion. `` In every race, we will attempt to make the right to abortion the major issue,'' declared NOW President <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>. The outcome is uncertain. National polls have indicated that few voters cast their ballots solely on the issue of abortion, and those who do split about evenly on both sides of the debate. However, given the court's ruling, `` We're dealing with a whole different environment,'' said <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballou </PERSON>, polling director for the <ORGANIZATION> Eagleton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` All those people in the middle are the ones that this change might impact.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> polling before the ruling found 23 percent support for more restrictions on abortion _ and 68 percent opposing restrictions. Moreover, many more abortion supporters held their views strongly. That is promising for Democratic gubernatorial nominee <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, who has pledged to veto any abortion restrictions. And it may trouble Republican <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, who has favored outlawing abortion except in most cases. `` If we can have a big win for <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, that makes a big statement,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Bowker </PERSON>. `` And if we can do well in the Assembly races, that makes an even bigger statement.'' Her plan of attack: A hit list of abortion opponents in the state Assembly, a series of pro-choice rallies across the state, radio advertising criticizing <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> on the issue _ and two new telephone lines at NOW state headquarters in <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, for his part, is playing down abortion's significance, with an aide saying Wednesday he does not see it as a central issue in the November election. In <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, pro-choice advocates say Democratic gubernatorial nominee <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s support for legal abortion has been equivocal; for example, he opposes public funding for abortion in most cases. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> faces Republican <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who opposes legalized abortion. `` It seems to me that if <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s going to win he has got to be much stronger on the issue of women's reproductive rights,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I think he's been scared by it. Nobody wins by being scared.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the issue has been raised mainly by <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> against <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, the front-runner in the polls. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> has had the city pay for abortions for poor women who have no other source of funds. He says <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, who opposes abortion personally, can not be trusted to continue the program. But <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s spokesman, said <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> would continue the abortion funding despite his personal beliefs. Said <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>: `` The mayor is spreading disniformation to try to heighten the fears of women.'' Abortion, he said, `` is not a mayoral issue.''
