<FIRST>r a PM-YellowstoneWolves     07-07 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Wolves,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wolf Awareness Program Draws Fire from Ranchers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ANGELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Howling wolves have n't been heard in Yellowstone National Park for decades, but even talk about them is enough to rile the ranchers and others surrounding the park The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s program to educate students across the country about the role of the wolf in the wild has raised fears by some that it could lead to the predator's return to <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s 2.2 million acres `` Wolves are fascinating animals and when you talk to people about them, you never get a ho-hum reaction. They always have a strong reaction one way or another,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarki </PERSON>, a ranger in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s Naturalist Division. `` They come with quite a bit of emotional baggage. We are trying to put some information in the hands of teachers and students: what -LRB- wolves -RRB- do, what their behavior is and what sort of role they have in the ecology,'' he said. `` It is not designed to sell a particular point of view, it is supposed to give them information so they can make up their minds on their own.'' Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, R-Wyo., is among those who see the wolf awareness program as a way to drum up support for the wolf's return to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> `` There is no other purpose for it but to promote reintroduction,'' <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. `` There are guys in there who are so -LRB- heated -RRB- up and so obsessed they ca n't even see.'' Turn-of-the-century eradication efforts by ranchers drove wolves from <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, and in recent years there has been a drive to return the animals to the park. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> and the rest of the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> congressional delegation long have opposed the plan, which has the support of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> officials. Those who want to return the wolves say they would prevent big-game herds from growing too large and overgrazing. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> and other foes fear the wolves would stray from <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> and prey on livestock on surrounding ranches. Rep. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Utah </LOCATION>, has sponsored legislation that would force the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to study how returning the wolves to the park would affect the environment. The <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> delegation is trying to derail that effort, too. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> brought a 13-month-old female wolf to the lawn outside the Capitol in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last month to dramatize his campaign. The wolf awareness program is being financed by donations from the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, several large corporations and one unidentified donor. It is meant to mesh with the park's `` Expedition Yellowstone'' program that prepares students for visits to the park. The financing bothers <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>. `` Forget the wolf aspect,'' he said. `` The issue is it is a bad precedent for interest groups to round up the money to do anything -LRB- through the Park Service -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said the arrangement amounts to federal government endorsement of a program that he says unfairly stresses the benefits of having wolves in the park without examining the impact of their presence as predators. The program, launched at the urging of former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mott </PERSON>, is designed to teach students about the wolf and its habits, not to promote their return to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, park officials say. The program teaches elementary and high school students about wolves and urges them to mimic the animals through classroom activities such as howling, which wolves use to communicate. Students also can join in the debate over the plan to return wolves to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> by staging a mock public meeting. `` They assume the positions of various special interest groups with parts in the debate,'' <PERSON> Zarki </PERSON> said. Not overlooked by the program is that wolves no longer lope through <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. `` It's not like we hide from the kids the fact the wolves are not here,'' he said. `` We try to deal with that and why. Most kids know animals are not as widespread as they used to be and people are in many cases responsible for that.'' <PERSON> Zarki </PERSON> conceded that the program may result in letters in favor of wolf reintroduction, but stressed it is not designed to do so. `` I'm not suggesting in the activities that they do that,'' he said. `` But if you look in the past ... there are many incidents where students focus on wildlife issues and write to legislators and action is taken. All we are trying to do is help kids learn a little bit more about wolves.''
