<HEAD>China's Conduct Raises Question of Whether to Stay in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hong Kong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwang </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> left a pharmaceutical plant, a five-story home and the good life behind in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> when the communists won the war 14 years ago and he fled to this British colony. He thought he had found a home. Then Chinese soldiers crushed pro-democracy demonstrations in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and he started searching for a new haven. <PERSON> Nansun </PERSON> <PERSON> Shi </PERSON>, a TV producer, was `` just too busy for politics'' before the crackdown. Now she heads a group teaching <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> residents about democracy and human rights. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is to assume control of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in 1997 under an agreement with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, but the heavy-handed suppression of dissent has shocked this colony of 5.7 million and is changing the attitudes of its people. Since the Chinese army assaulted Tiananmen Square the night of June 3-4, hundreds of thousands of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> residents have put aside political apathy and taken to the streets in protest. More than 650,000 signed a petition for democratic reforms and a bill of rights, and demanding that <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> residents be given the right to live in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Callers to radio talk shows have proposed independence for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, while others say it should buy some islands to accommodate its people. Some residents have started an `` underground railroad'' to get dissidents out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Xuexin </PERSON>, a waiter at the Good Taste Restaurant in the <LOCATION> Happy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> district, expressed the feelings of many: `` I'm terrified of what will happen when the Communists come. My whole family is; neighbors, too. `` I fled <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during the Cultural Revolution. I swam here and risked my neck. After 1978 and <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, I had a little hope. Then there was the massacre on <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. Now I know Communists will never change.'' Fear is not confined to Chinese residents. Many of the 100,000 Westerners in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> also worry. `` This is home,'' said <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, 44. `` I've spent half my married life here. I had one of my sons here. This is where I want to be, but if we do n't leave now and it collapses around us after 1997, we might just be too old.'' Under the 1984 agreement between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> promises to keep <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s capitalist system intact for 50 years after 1997. It also agreed to an unspecified degree of political `` autonomy,'' currently being negotiated. After the bloodshed in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and ensuing mass arrests, many people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> lost faith that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would keep its word. Thousands want to emigrate, but some like Ms. <PERSON> Shi </PERSON> say they are willing to stay and fight. Educated in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as a member of a well-off <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> family, she spent her teens `` wearing bobby socks and reading Seventeen magazine.'' She returned to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in her 20s, got a public relations job and soon began reporting on high society for television. Later, she moved to producing movies and TV shows. `` I never was political at all,'' she said. `` I had a sense of what was right, but that covered all spheres. I just did n't think about politics. That's not what we were taught to do.'' When <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s army attacked the students, she said, `` I was ... shocked so I could n't speak, possibly because it was such a simple issue, which is so rare these days. It's so black and white. It's so clear who was right and who was wrong.'' After taking part in demonstrations, organizing a concert and working on a song for the pro-democracy movement, Ms. <PERSON> Shi </PERSON> said, it seemed to her that people knew well enough what they were protesting but not what they were fighting for. `` We were shouting ` democracy,' ` freedom,' ` human rights,' but nobody knew what that meant,'' she said. `` I figured I had to find out.'' The result was a series of seminars on the topic by leading <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> academics. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lau </PERSON>, a nurse who attended a recent Sunday of lectures at the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the program opened her mind. `` It made me want to educate myself,'' she said, holding a filled notebook. `` Our system teaches us how to be good workers, but not good thinkers.'' <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON>, a 65-year-old taxi driver who fled <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> in 1954, said the crackdown in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> `` woke people up. It taught the young people about the Communists.'' `` They said the same thing in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> in the 1950s: ` You can stay capitalist; we need your help,' all that stuff,'' he said. `` Then they came in and took the factories away and locked up the capitalists. It's going to be the same story here.'' Tan, the pharmacist, said his South Vietnamese passport will make moving more difficult. `` It gets so maddening,'' he said. `` I struggled here for 10 years and finally am making a little money in real estate. Then this happens, the market goes soft and my wife starts telling me it's time to find a new country.
