<HEAD>Former Candidate for Haitian Presidency Arrested in Bank Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Haitian exile who ran for president of his island nation in 1987 was arrested Thursday on charges he operated a bogus bank that may have bilked customers out of tens of millions of dollars, a federal prosecutor said. <PERSON> Clemard </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, who was granted asylum in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> nine years ago, and three others purported to run the <ORGANIZATION> Banque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D'Haiti </ORGANIZATION> from a home in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> and a mortgage company from a luxury apartment overlooking Central Park in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, authorities said. Neither concern was authorized to operate in the state. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said the victims of the scheme, which ran for about two years, ranged from drug dealers to international financiers. `` What makes this operation so unusual was the brazenness, the chutzpah,'' <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said. `` They never moved out of a location, they never left town. That makes it a little extraordinary.'' Investigators will not know how many people and financial institutions were cheated and how much money the scams earned until records seized by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents during raids Thursday are examined, <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said. The bank apparently cheated its customers out of tens of millions of dollars, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON>, adding `` we do n't really have a handle on it.'' In one complex transaction, the bank recently issued bogus multimillion-dollar letters of credit payable to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the economic m