<HEAD>Estate Attorneys Argue False Advertising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for photographer <PERSON> Ansel </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' estate argued in federal court Thursday that publishers of a book of <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' pictures taken for the federal government during World War II engaged in false advertising They sought to ban the sale of a calendar and desk reference book based on the same material, which is entitled, `` The Mural Project'' and said the book publishers wrongly used <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' name to sell their book. Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mustin </PERSON>, representing the trustees of the <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> estate, said the trustees did not publish the pictures in question because they felt the quality was not representative of <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' work. The publishers `` are in it for the money,'' <PERSON> Mustin </PERSON> argued. `` The trustees are in it for the reputation of <PERSON> Ansel </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. My clients want to preserve the integrity and quality of the work. But attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallen </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Day </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>, said the only reason the quality of the pictures is not good is because the negatives are unavailable. The authors of `` The Mural Project'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Armor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, claim the negatives are being hidden by the trustees. The pictures themselves are in the public domain and can be purchased from the government for about $ 10 apiece. They were shot in 1941 and 1942 when <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> was working for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, photographing park scenes to be blown up for murals in public buildings. The murals were never made. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Ickes </PERSON> had hired <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> for $ 22.22 a day plus expenses, and the photos became government property. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> said there is no dispute that the photos are in the public domain and <PERSON> Mustin </PERSON> said the trustees are not challenging publication of the book itself. `` We are not challenging the book in these proceedings because we understand it is already in the stream of commerce,'' he said. `` The toothpaste is out of the tube.'' But they seek to stop distribution of the calendar and datebook and further use of <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' name in advertising. The ad in question described the photos as `` The finding of an unknown body of work by <PERSON> Ansel </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>'' and compared it to the discovery of `` an unknown play by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>, an unknown symphony by <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>.'' The trustees claimed this was misleading. But the judge disagreed. `` The fact is that this was and is a commissioned body of work and it was not available until the ferreting out by Armor and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>,'' he said. `` I'm not inclined to believe from a practical standpoint that this is misleading advertising.'' The legal arguments on further points of dispute were continued until Friday afternoon. The judge said he would take the matter under submission before issuing a ruling.
