<HEAD>Sugar Production on the Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar production is rising after a slump because of last year's drought, according to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> forecasters. Total production in the 1989-90 crop year that begins Sept. 1 is expected to be about 7.3 million tons, up 5.6 percent from 1988-89 output estimated at 6.91 million tons. Prompted by prices guaranteed under the government's system of supports and protective quotas that limit the entry of cheaper foreign sugar, domestic output climbed to a record 7.33 million tons in 1987-88. In 1985-86, by comparison, total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar production was barely 6 million tons. With improved growing conditions, sugar production in the coming year could match or exceed the record level of two years ago. Beet sugar production, forecast at 3.9 million tons, would be up 11 percent from the drought-reduced level of 3.51 million tons this season, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Cane sugar, which rose to a record of just under 3.4 million tons in 1988-89, is forecast at about the same in 1989-90. `` According to field information through mid-June, beet planting and early development have generally gone well throughout the beet areas,'' the report said. `` This is in sharp contrast to last year when a series of spring weather problems was followed by drought in key eastern growing areas.'' The report added: `` Drought, particularly in the non-irrigated <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> of western <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, and disease and weather problems in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, lowered yields.'' These three states accounted for 55 percent of total sugar beet harvested acreage in 1988-89 and 51 percent of the total beet tonnage. That compared with 56 percent and 54 percent, respectively, during the three previous seasons. Yields would have been even lower had it not been for good growing conditions late in the season, excellent harvesting weather and higher rates of sugar recovered from the beets, the report said. Farmers are expected to have about 1.3 million acres of beets for harvest in 1989-90, about the same as this season. The area for sugar cane harvest is expected to be about 807,000 acres, up 10 percent from 1988-89, reflecting small increases in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Mainland production is forecast at about 2.45 million tons, and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s output, 940,000 tons. `` <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s sugar cane acreage continues to contract, with only 77,000 acres likely to be harvested this season, compared with almost 100,000 in the early 1980s,'' the report said. `` Alternative land use continues to encroach on traditional sugar acreage.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has turned into a growing market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> duck feet and tongues, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Deep-fried duck feet in oyster sauce, and duck tongues soaked in fish sauce or stir-fried with seasonal vegetables are some of the dishes offered by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> restaurants in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said The demand for whole ducklings, feet, tongues and gizzards is so brisk that the local supply ca n't keep up. As a result, the agency said in the July issue of AgExporter magazine, a number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> poultry plants have built a thriving export business on supplying the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> duck market. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoben </PERSON>, an executive with one processing plant, <ORGANIZATION> Concord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concord </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> duck processors sold more than 4 million pounds of duck feet to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> alone last year. `` All of our duck feet and tongues are exported to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hoben </PERSON> said `` That market represents 4 percent of our total business, and it is a very important market for <ORGANIZATION> Concord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION>.'' Aggressive market promotion in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has been part of the reason for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> success in the duck market. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Targeted Export Assistance Program, which helps finance approved overseas promotional efforts, has been particularly effective. For example, the program financed a booklet featuring recipes for duck feet, tongue and duckling recipes for the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> market, available there in both Chinese and English, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ice cream production jumped sharply in May, just in time for the summer rush, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. With production at 79.8 million gallons, that was up 16 percent from April and 3 percent from May of last year, the department's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday And that was only `` hard'' ice cream. There were no estimates for soft versions produced by machines across the country. But the report did show that ice milk production, at 37.4 million gallons in May, was up 20 percent from April and 9 percent from a year earlier. Sherbet production was 5.4 million gallons, up 26 percent and 20 percent, respectively. Frozen yogurt output was estimated at 6.74 million gallons in May, virtually the same as in April. No year-earlier figures were available.
