<HEAD>Marine Corps Signs Up for Correspondence Courses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Marines guarding the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies abroad are often limited in off-duty activities, but now there's something for their minds _ college by mail The Marine Security Guard Battalion reached an agreement recently with <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to offer an associate-degree program to the 1,450 Marines guarding 141 embassies and consulates around the world. Taking classes by mail will help relieve boredom in such hardship posts as the embassy in <LOCATION> Ouagadougou </LOCATION>, the capital of the west African nation of <PERSON> Burkina </PERSON> <PERSON> Faso </PERSON>, Marine Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Vindich </PERSON> said. `` There's absolutely nothing there,'' said <PERSON> Vindich </PERSON>, the battalion's education officer. Also, Marines stationed at embassies and consulates in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are restricted by a non-fraternization policy, while those in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> ca n't leave the compound because of the country's civil war. `` A lot of these places are really isolated,'' <PERSON> Vindich </PERSON> said. `` We're providing an educational opportunity and we're also giving them something to do.'' <PERSON> Vindich </PERSON> said Marines in the elite, all-volunteer battalion generally spend 15 months in a hardship post and then 15 months at a less rigorous embassy or consulate. More than 400 Marines serving in embassies and consulates already take courses, but their efforts toward degrees have been largely unstructured, he said. `` They were out there spinning their wheels. You talk college credits and semester hours and that kind of thing, it boggles the mind of a 19-year-old kid just out of high school, 10,000 miles from home,'' <PERSON> Vindich </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Quantico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. Under an agreement reac