<FIRST>r w PM-CruiseShips     07-07 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Ships,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Eyes U.S.-Owned Ships Carrying Americans Under Foreign
Flags</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal safety officials want the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to be allowed to regulate luxury cruise ships that are owned by Americans, carry Americans and use American ports but fly under foreign flags. `` We're not in a position to protect the lives of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen in these types of vessels, and something's got to be done about it,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday issued several recommendations that would affect more than 80 cruise ships that dock at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports. Only two or three such cruise ships are registered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, board investigators said. The board, which is preparing a more extensive report on the cruise ship industry in a few months, recently concluded an investigation into a fire that caused a near-catastrophe aboard a Bahamian-flagged vessel off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast 16 months ago. The board concluded that a lack of maintenance, lack of fire-fighting procedures and poor crew training caused the fire aboard the Scandinavian Star, which was carrying 700 people back to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, from a two-day Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> cruise. The board said failure of a fire-fighting system and the inability of crew members, who spoke a variety of languages, to communicate with each other and with passengers contributed to the emergency. `` It was only sheer luck'' that no injuries or deaths occurred aboard the 10,000-ton vessel owned by Sea Escape of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON>. `` This is an invitation to disaster,'' said <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON>. He said U.S.-owned cruise ships are registered in several different countries because of the high expenses involved in meeting requirements as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag carriers. <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> DeChello </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escape </ORGANIZATION>, said the company had no immediate comment on the board decision. She said the company operates four 10,000-ton ships, each carrying 950 to 1,100 passengers on cruises out of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. In the last decade, the board has investigated five major fires aboard cruise vessels, three of them on Sea Escape ships. One in 1984 killed one passenger and one crew member. Scores of people have been injured, mostly from smoke inhalation. No other deaths have been reported in accidents aboard American-operated cruise ships, but a Cuban ship captain and two sailors were killed when the U.S.-owned Celebration cut their freighter in half Feb. 10. The board is seeking court orders to force witnesses to give testimony in its investigation of the Celebration accident. The ship's owner, <ORGANIZATION> Carnival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, has refused to cooperate in the safety investigation, saying it is responding only to authorities in <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, where the vessel is registered. In Thursday's action, the board asked the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates civilian shipping, to seek legislation that would give it authority over the safety of cruise ships. The board also called for smoke detectors that automatically shut down ventilation systems so smoke wo n't spread through passenger cabins; improved testing of fire extinguishing systems; back-up generators for fire alarms, public address systems and smoke detectors, and several other safety improvements for all cruise ships. The safety board has no authority to impose its recommendations. The board said the Scandinavian Star fire on March 15, 1988, started with an oil leak. It said fuel pipe packing seals and deflector sleeves that would have prevented the oil from being ignited were deteriorated and had not been replaced. `` I'm afraid this ship was being managed more like a night club than a vessel,'' said board member <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, who led the investigation into the fire. The ship, which was towed to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> after the fire was put out, has since been repaired and is back in operation.
