<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> is getting used to his roommates' comings and goings, now that they've settled in behind the cereal boxes. About six weeks ago, two <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> wrens flew in through his unscreened kitchen window. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> then noticed some sticks and twigs near the cereal boxes, the beginnings of a nest, and he decided to let them stay. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> tried to help the birds by leaving a torn cotton ball. But they preferred their own materials, and would n't use it, he said. As the nest neared completion, the mother wren, a small brown bird about three inches long, became more familiar with <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>. She did not easily frighten when he went into the kitchen, he said. `` After a while, she got used to me,'' he said. Once the nest was completed, the brown bird laid a set of blue-speckled eggs. Within two weeks, five eggs hatched and the baby birds began begging for food. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said he's awaiting the day when the mother bird begins teaching her chicks to fly. He's ready for his kitchen to become a training ground.
