<DATELINE>STORRS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION>, the political climate has improved for a dog. Twenty years ago, the student <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted to sell <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON>, the school's Siberian husky mascot, because he represented the establishment. But later this month, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON>, the latest in a line of huskies that have represented the college, may win back his ancestors' status as symbol of school spirit. <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Omega </ORGANIZATION>, a coeducational service fraternity, has asked the board of trustees to restore <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON>'s status. The board is expected to take up the issue July 14. The huskies were named after an early <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> governor, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumbull </PERSON>. Many of the dogs figure prominently in the lore, especially <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> IV which survived a dog-nabbing by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> students. In 1969, the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to sell the mascot was protested by about 2,500 students. <PERSON> Alpha </PERSON> <PERSON> Phi </PERSON> <PERSON> Omega </PERSON> took responsibility for the dog; <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> lives with a family off campus. Fraternity members say if the trustees name the newest <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> as school mascot, they will trot him out for events. They plan to show him off at sporting and social events, and will lobby for him as grand marshal of the Homecoming Day parade.
