<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Leaders,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Japanese Leaders Asked to Focus on `Real Issues'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese leaders are urged in a new report to stress to their people that both sides have more to gain through cooperation than ruthless rivalry. `` But unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can come to terms with its fear of ` being taken' by the Japanese'' and the Japanese abandon `` their mercantilist view of the world, such cooperation remains beyond reach,'' says the report published by the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. Leaders of `` both <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> need to foster greater public understanding of the real issues,'' especially on defense, said the 68-page study issued this week, entitled `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1989.'' Three previous reports in the annual series dealt in detail with individual economic disputes between the two countries. The latest study focused more on managing the relationship to prevent conflicts from overshadowing basic advantages. `` Political leaders in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> should take the lead in working to eliminate misconceptions and reaffirm the basic premises of U.S.-Japan cooperation, lest misunderstanding lead to bad legislation,'' the report said. `` Although fundamentals supporting the U.S.-Japan relationship are almost universally positive, these can be quickly forgotten in bouts of name-calling,'' it cautioned. The report voiced concern over `` the rapid growth of a cottage industry of Japan-bashers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who warn us that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> represents a greater threat than the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to our economic and security interests. ... Their various allegations, if left unanswered, can erode the relationship ... leading to the self-fulfilling prophecy syndrome.'' Tracing what it called `` real issues,'' the study said, `` Japanese political leaders will have to make unprecedented efforts to present <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s defense responsibilities in a straightforward manner and stress the importance of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -LRB- military -RRB- bases to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government officials must ... educate the American public on Japanese contributions to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense ... -LRB- and -RRB- make clear that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for its own national security, not simply to defend <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' The study said both countries should correct domestic problems creating U.S.-Japanese friction.
