<HEAD>Exxon Agrees to Permit State to Interview its Records Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> said it will make employees available for questioning in the state investigation of how some copies of company records on the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> oil spill were destroyed Company officials said Thursday that the destroyed records were backup computer files and that `` all primary records and documents'' on the spill remained on other computer tapes in company possession. `` I can assure you of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s continued cooperation in assisting your office to fully understand the circumstances and insignificance of the computer backup-tape matter,'' <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> lawyer E.D. <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> wrote <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Baily </PERSON>. <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> demanded Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> allow the state to take depositions from employees involved in the records destruction, which <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> says was an accident. He termed it `` potentially a loss of devastating proportions.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON>, a spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to supply affidavits next week from employees who handled the records. <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> said he hoped to get the depositions under way within two weeks. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, an Exxon spokesman in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said the affidavits are part of an internal company report on the tape incident, which will be provided to the state. The oil company is under state and federal court orders to preserve its records of the March 24 tanker spill in which nearly 11 million gallons of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> crude oil fouled Prince <PERSON> William