<HEAD>`Outer Limits' Narrator Vic Perrin Dies At Age 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor and announcer <PERSON> Vic </PERSON> <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>, who provided the spooky voice that told viewers of `` The Outer Limits'' TV show that their sets had just been taken over by mysterious forces, has died of cancer. He was 73. <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>, who died Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, was known to millions in the 1960s for saying at the beginning of each `` Outer Limits'' show: `` There is nothing wrong with your television set. ... Do not attempt to adjust the picture. ... We are controlling transmission.'' He would come on again at the show's conclusion to `` return control'' of the set to the viewer and leave the audience with a moral for that week's episode of the science fiction anthology series. <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Menomonee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> before moving West in 1940. In <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, he embarked on a career in radio that was to make his voice, if not his face or name, known to millions. His worked as a radio announcer for both <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and was a regular on such shows as the radio version of `` Gunsmoke,'' `` One Man's Family,'' `` Fort Laramie'' and `` Yours Truly <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Dollar </PERSON>.'' In 1956, <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON> joined `` The <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workshop </ORGANIZATION>'' a short-lived but critically praised series that broadcast experimental dramas and classics, including a narration by <PERSON> Aldous </PERSON> <PERSON> Huxley </PERSON> of his `` Brave New World.'' Later, <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON> appeared regularly on such TV shows as `` Dragnet,'' `` Mission Impossible,'' `` Gunsmoke,'' `` Star Trek,'' `` Big Valley'' and `` Maverick.'' He also was the announcer on several commercials, but refused to go before the cameras to sell products, saying that `` if they see me in a commercial, they ca n't believe me as an actor.'' <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>'s voice can still be heard on reruns of `` The Outer Limits,'' which originally aired form 1963 to 1965, and at <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s The Spaceship Earth and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pavilion </ORGANIZATION> attractions. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Rita </PERSON>; a son; and a stepson. A memorial service was scheduled for Wednesday in <LOCATION> Studio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
