<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was nearing a final decision on a proposal that would give most senior federal officials pay increases of 25 percent, matching a salary hike he has already advocated for federal judges, White House officials said today. But while the announcement was expected by day's end, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> still had not signed off on details of the proposals, said one official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. `` It's still on his desk,'' the official said. Both The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would formally ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today for the pay raise for top officials and would couple it with a proposed ban on congressional honoraria. Sources said the proposal now on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s desk does not contain a specific pay raise proopsal for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to go along with the proposed limit on outside income. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has advocated pay raises in general for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but has decided to steer clear of becoming ensnared in what is always a poltically treacherous issue on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, deciding instead to let <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> resolve the matter itself, the sources said. An announcement on the pay issue seemed likely today as the president sought to clear away unfinished business before embarking Sunday on a nine-day trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that will include the seven-nation economic summit in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s pay package would include increases of as much as 200 percent for a small number of `` critically skilled'' federal worke