<HEAD>Louisiana Wants To Test 1973 Court Ruling On Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> has asked district attorneys to enforce a criminal law that was on the books before the landmark 1973 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision giving women the right to have abortions. The resolution, which does not have the force of law, was approved 81-13 Thursday night. It now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which will give speedy passage, said Rep. <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. `` This will allow the court to face squarely the issue of whether to uphold or overturn the 1973 <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision,'' said <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, who serves as floor leader for issues pressed by fundamentalist churches. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said Monday's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling, in which it upheld <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>'s right to regulate abortion, invited states to test the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> ruling. <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, like <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, prohibits the use of public funds, employees or facilities for abortions. A check with the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> showed that <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s pre-Roe statutes were never ruled unconstitutional, said <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. The chief law, said <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, prohibits anyone from performing an abortion and carries a penalty of up to 10 years in prison. `` We were enjoined by the federal courts from enforcing it because of <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>,'' he said. `` Our resolution will have the effect of sending the district attorneys to federal district court, asking that the injunction be lifted.'' Opponents said <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> wanted <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> to flout the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are saying with this resolution that we are going to go above the court,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Kip </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>. `` This is not just to provoke a ruling from the court. This is asking district attorneys to throw doctors in jail.'' Rep. <PERSON> Alphonse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the Monday ruling did not disturb a woman's right to have an abortion in the first trimester. `` Women have that right,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> legislature is in special session to ratify the extension of a state sales tax. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> noted that Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> did not include abortion legislation in his official call for the six-day session. Legislators can not draft laws on topics not covered in the official call. However, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimos </PERSON> said the resolution was not a law. `` This urges district attorneys to act. We can offer urge and request resolutions in this session.'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said he believes the district attorneys will cooperate in a state that has such strong anti-abortion sentiment.
