<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several bottles of cheap wine tainted with a soapy solution or broken glass have been found recently in areas frequented by transients, but no one has been injured, police said. The tamperings might have been attempts to harm the homeless, but if so, they were clumsy ones, police said. Officers noted that the bottle seals had obviously been broken and the caps simply screwed back on. The bottles were full. `` No one, under any circumstances, would want to have anything to do with bottles like that,'' Sgt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glaus </PERSON> said. `` We made an assumption, and we think it's a big assumption, that there might be an intent to do harm.'' The first three bottles were reported by a woman on May 27 at Vera Cruz Park, an area often frequented by homeless people in this seaside community 90 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The three bottles of <ORGANIZATION> Boones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strawberry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> contained a soapy liquid, <PERSON> Glaus </PERSON> said. The liquid has not been tested. Last Saturday, three more tainted bottles, containing small bits of broken glass, were found near railroad tracks and near a pathway to a beach often used by homeless people, <PERSON> Glaus </PERSON> said. Police also had a report from a man who said he found some wine that looked tainted June 27 but had thrown the bottles away.
