<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations today asked <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to present President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s arms reduction initiatives at the East-West disarmament talks. Officials said they hope details of the proposal will be submitted before next week, when the current round of talks is to end. `` We're pressing strongly that they present the framework of the proposals by the end of this round on July 13,'' said <PERSON> Wlodzimierz </PERSON> <PERSON> Konarski </PERSON>, Polish delegation chief at the talks on conventional armed forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In May, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> support for a proposal to reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to 275,000 on each side. That would require the Soviets to withdraw and demobilize 325,000 Red Army soldiers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also proposed limits on tanks, armored troop carriers and artillery pieces. And he said the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is willing to expand its proposal to include, for the first time, land-based combat aircraft and helicopters from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to the Soviet Ural mountains. Western experts at the Western alliance headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> said last month they would formally present <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact when talks open for their third round on Sept. 5. <PERSON> Konarski </PERSON>, speaking for the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc, was optimistic about progress but mentioned some differences. `` We all now agree that a future agreement should cover six categories of conventional armed forces even though a formal proposal of our Western partners to this effect has not yet been submitted,'' <PERSON> Konarski </PERSON> told reporters. He said if the main obstacles were overcome during the next round `` then the agreement could indeed be concluded within 12 months,'' the timetable suggested by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> opened the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks on conventional arms reductions March 9 proposing each military bloc reduce three kinds of weapons _ tanks, artillery and armored personnel carriers. The Soviet military bloc countered with a far broader, less specific proposal to reduce six kinds of weapons 10 percent to 15 percent below present levels by 1994, then add a further 25 percent reduction by 1997 before moving to only defensive forces in 2000. Reductions in aircraft are among points of disagreement. Western delegates say aircraft are difficult to count and can be redeployed in any disarmed zone within hours. <PERSON> Konarski </PERSON> made clear the issue is of vital importance for the future of the talks. `` The issue of aircraft remains to be solved as a matter of priority,'' he said.
