<SECOND>AM-Baltics-Land,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Republic Steps Beyond Kremlin in Decollectivizing Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The parliament of Soviet <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> passed a law this week that goes a step beyond national legislation in giving land back to farmers after decades of collectization, newspapers reported Friday. The law stops short of total decollectivization, but would _ without charge _ give farmers the land they farm now with the right to pass it on to heirs, according to <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Litva </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily. The law does not allow farmers to sell land, a step the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> might view as a violation of the communist ban on ownership of major private property. Soviet farms have been owned by the state or by state-controlled collectives since 1929-30. The bill could strengthen efforts by the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lativa </LOCATION> to become more autonomous. They were occupied and annexed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1940. It was not clear whether the national legislature, the Supreme Soviet, would try to override the new Lithuanian law in the same way it vetoed a law passed by the legislature of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> last fall proclaiming autonomy in the republic. The Lithuanian law, which has not yet been published in full, went beyond national legislation passed in April allowing farmers to rent land on 50-year leases with a right to pass it on to descendants. Farmers have been slow to take out leases, fearing the reforms could be overturned, according to poll results published in April by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper Pravda. The Lithuanian law, according to the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, said `` land, granted to the peasant for use with no fixed term, with rights of inheritance and without payment, does not include the right to sale.'' Activists in the Lithuanian grassroots political group <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION> had been pushing for more radical legislation that would have granted farmers the right to buy and sell land, but a compromise was reached in the republic's legislature, said <PERSON> Zhilvenas </PERSON> <PERSON> Glebus </PERSON>, reached by telephone in the Lithuanian capital of <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>. The Lithuanian law will go into effect Aug. 1, according to <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION> workers, quoting the Sovietskaya Litva article.
