<HEAD>N.C. Attorney General Calls for Federal Probe Of Gasoline Price-Fixing</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DENNIS PATTERSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s attorney general called today for a federal investigation of price-fixing by major oil companies, saying a state probe showed either greed or collusion is behind recent price increases. `` Greed is n't illegal, but price fixing is, and that has been the focus of our investigation here in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>,'' Attorney General <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said the oil companies have blamed the wreck of the Exxon Valdez in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and normal market forces such as increased summer demand and higher crude oil prices for the rapid increase in gasoline prices over the past four months. But <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> spill `` was simply a small drop in a very large bucket.'' He said crude oil prices have not affected prices for other petroleum products, such as heating oil and diesel fuel. `` The oil companies have put forward other excuses for the simultaneous gas price increases, but their arguments have more holes than the hull of the Exxon Valdez,'' <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. He said investigators tracked prices for three months from retailers back through wholesale terminals and the major out-of-state suppliers, finding that price increases took place at the refinery level, while profits of wholesalers and retailers remained stable. <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said he had forwarded the state's investigation and a formal request for a federal investigation to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> official said he also will ask his counterparts in other states at a meeting this weekend to form a task force to examine the price fixing allegations. `` I anticipate we will get a good response from the federal government,'' <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. `` We can demonstrate with other states a general outcry around the country, and when you have a widespread public outcry, you usually can get a positive response. `` It is awfully difficult to prove price-fixing. It always has been,'' <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. `` But we're certainly going to give it our best shot.''
