<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> will send a representative to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to secure the release of an American photojournalist arrested by the Afghan government, an official said Friday. Arrangements were being made to obtain the release of <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, a free-lance photographer on assignment for <ORGANIZATION> Time-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said an embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Things are still on track,'' the official said. He said he could not estimate how long it would take for arrangements to be completed. The <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government said July 1 that <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, would be released without trial if the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sent an official to take him home. It said the decision was made in response to an appeal from <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, 42, was arrested June 8 for entering <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> without legal documents and in the company of Moslem rebels fighting the Soviet-backed government. He had been covering the Afghan civil war from <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the base for many Moslem guerrilla groups. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> has made several trips into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with the guerrillas. Under emergency laws in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, he could have been jailed for entering the country without legal documents, for which there is no maximum sentence. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> was closed in January, before the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> completed its troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.
