<HEAD>Aquino to Seek Investment, Political Support in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Buoyed by the promise of billions in foreign aid, President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> leaves Saturday on a three-nation West European tour in search of financial and political support for her troubled country. Philippine officials say Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> will try to exploit her image as savior of Filipino democracy to encourage greater trade and investment to help cope with problems of poverty, communist insurgency and a $ 28 billion foreign debt. She also hopes to dispel European fears that her government has been laggard in fulfilling the pledge to protect human rights made when she was swept to power in the 1986 uprising that toppled <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' authoritarian administration. `` I would like to deliver to the people and countries of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> the message that the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is committed to democracy, which our people restored in a very unique way, by peaceful means,'' she said in a radio broadcast this week. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> will travel to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, then to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to join bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution, and finally to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s trip, her second to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as president, follows a commitment Wednesday by industrial countries and international financial institutions to provide $ 3.5 billion in 1989 in aid for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. As part of the program, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> promised to triple its aid to about $ 350 million a year. The visit represents another step in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s efforts to expand trade and contacts with <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and broaden its foreign policy, which traditionally focused on its former colonial power, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In February, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> expressed support for Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> but added it was concerned about mounting human rights violations. Human rights groups, including <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, accuse the military and government-backed vigilante groups of widespread torture, assassinations and illegal abductions of suspected rebels on flimsy evidence. Officials say Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> will argue her government is committed to human rights but faces a serious threat from the 23,000-member communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which has been waging a 20-year war to establish a Marxist state. Ten policemen and soldiers have been slain in the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> area in the last two weeks in attacks which the military blames on communist rebels. Opposition Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> said Friday that Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s trip will reinforce the country's image as a borrower and a beggar He said Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> was leaving behind a nation in turmoil. On the eve of her departure, the government announced the arrest of a soldier in the 1988 murder of a left-wing activist and the attempted slaying of a companion in one of the country's best-known human rights cases. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> said Constable 2nd Class <PERSON> Dioscoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambagay </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, was arrested and warrants have been issued for two more soldiers in the slaying of leftist <PERSON> Reynaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> and an attempt on the life of <PERSON> Hilario </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> in March 1988.
