<HEAD>U.N. Refugee Flights to Capital Halted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has halted refugee flights to the capital of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> because resettlement camps are overflowing, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Friday. The refugees, most of them supporters of the guerrilla movement that fought for 23 years against South African rule, have stayed in the camps around <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> longer than the seven days the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees had planned on. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckhard </PERSON> said the refugees are reluctant to leave and go to their home villages in the north, where the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has most of its support, because they fear Namibian police will harass them. Refugees who have been flown into northern cities have moved out of the temporary settlement camps and those flights will continue, <PERSON> Eckhard </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has arranged for representatives in the camps near <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> to travel to the north, see the situation and report back, with the hope that the refugees in the camps will be persuaded to leave. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said 16,244 of the 41,000 Namibians registered with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees have returned so far, mostly from <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> camps in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. All refugees are to return by Sept. 15, the end of the registration period for voting in elections planned for November. He said two planeloads of Namibians from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> were due to arrive on July 18 and July 24, and that small groups have returned from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> said before the independence process began that it was caring for some 80,000 refugees with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> aid, but there has been no explanation for the change in numbers. About 150 refugees who returned this week had been held prisoner by <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> in Angolan camps. In response to their tales of torture and allegations that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is holding hundreds more prisoners, <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special representative in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, appealed Friday for all prisoners on both sides to be freed under terms of U.N. Resolution 435. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has withdrawn all but 1,500 of its troops from the territory it has ruled since 1915 and has agreed to grant <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence. But <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, the South African administrator of the territory until it becomes independent, said Wednesday he will not free about 30 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> prisoners held by the police until a full accounting is made of all prisoners who may still be in the hands of the guerrilla movement.
