<HEAD>Drunken-Driving Roadblocks Unconstitutional, Rhode Island Court Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drunken-driving roadblocks violate the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> constitution even if they are operated under guidelines the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has implied are acceptable, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled Friday. The roadblocks are an invasion of privacy under the state constitution's declaration of rights, which is stricter than the federal <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> of Rights, the high court said in a 3-2 decision. Police officials said the ruling would have little practical effect because few <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> police departments use roadblocks. But one police chief who favors them said the ruling could lead to more injuries and deaths from drunken drivers. `` How about the innocent people's rights?'' said <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Choquette </PERSON>, who used the roadblocks until doubts about their constitutionality arose last summer. `` I do n't think it's giving a fair shake to the innocent person walking down the street.'' Narragansett Police Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON> said his department abandoned the practice a couple of years ago because roadblocks were not cost-effective, and <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> Police Capt. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> agreed that his officers could catch more drunken drivers by patrolling than by setting up a fixed roadblock. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingstown </LOCATION> Police Chief <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Vespia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he does not use roadblocks because he agrees with the court's reasoning. `` The concept of reasonable grounds to stop someone is n't there when you set up roadblocks to stop everybody,'' he said. The ruling voided the conviction of <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Pimental </PERSON>, who was found guilty of refusing to submit to a chemical test after he was stopped by <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> police during a roadblock Oct. 10, 1986. Although the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has not ruled on drunken-driving roadblocks, it did imply in a 1979 ruling that they would be acceptable under certain limited conditions. The justices agreed that the <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> roadblock would probably pass federal muster because police gave adequate notice, conducted it with minimal interference to the public and had limited discretion in deciding which cars to stop. However, Chief Justice <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> and two other justices said the state constitution bars roadblocks no matter how carefully they are operated. `` It is well beyond dispute that drunk drivers are a grave menace to the public and that stronger measures are needed to cope with this problem,'' <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> wrote. `` However, it would shock and offend the framers of the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> constitution if we were to hold that the guarantees against unreasonable and warrantless searches and seizures should be subordinated to the interest of efficient law enforcement.'' Justice <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shea </PERSON>, in dissent, said the majority did not have the `` justifiable and principled rationale'' it needed to depart from previous <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings. `` The minimal intrusion on the driver's privacy rights is reasonable and fully within the safeguards provided by ... the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> constitution,'' <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> wrote.
