<HEAD>Bulgaria Decrees Conscription for Emergencies as Ethnic Turks Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has issued a decree empowering authorities to conscript civilians to work in `` emergencies'' threatening the economy, apparently to counter a massive exodus of ethnic Turks. Authorities can send civilians to work anywhere in the country under the decree. Western diplomats and journalists who have visited areas where ethnic Turks lived say many towns and villages are nearly empty and fields remain unharvested. Austrian TV showed footage this week from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> of fields strewn with unharvested fruit and rotting vegetables. About 100,000 ethnic Turks have fled to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> in recent months, claiming they have been victimized by an assimilation campaign begun in 1984 which bans them from using their Turkish names, speaking Turkish or practicing Islamic rites. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> issued the decree on June 30, but it was not published until this week, Western diplomats said. Excerpts were made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. According to the decree, men aged 18 to 60 and women 18 to 55 can be mobilized nationwide or on a regional basis. It did not say for how long. People can be called up `` to ensure the necessary manpower and equipment in emergencies or natural calamities presenting considerable difficulties to the national economy and to the country.'' Invalids, pregnant women and mothers of children under 7 are exempt. `` Those who evade civilian mobilization or without a plausible reason fail to fulfill their assignments will be fined'' up to $ 3,000, the decree said. Mobilized civilians will be paid according to undisclosed norms established by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, it said. Diplomats in <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> said they have no information tha