<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security forces armed with emergency laws arrested at least 49 suspected Sinhalese radicals as continuing civil unrest claimed 25 lives, the government said Friday. Military and police, operating under new shoot-on-sight orders, killed eight radicals in skirmishes when they made the arrests, the information department said. Ten radicals were injured, it said. Extremists of the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> killed 12 civilians, three soldiers and a police officer since Wednesday, the statement said. No further details were given to the press, working under strict censorship laws clamped Thursday to coincide with a government crackdown on the anti-government extremists. A nationwide emergency was imposed June 20. The country's two main newspapers Friday warned that censoring the news fuels rumors. Critical editorials in <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and The Sun newspapers were submitted to government censors. Sources at the dailies said the editorials were approved without changes. `` Tongues wag in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> ... censorship will be of no avail,'' said The Island. `` The danger of censorship is that all fantastic rumors tend to gain more credibility.'' The Sun said: `` What must necessarily be stressed is the futility of the exercise, as censorship often in the past turned out to be counterproductive. With the technical stoppage of news and views, the flow of rumor, gossip and electronic tele-talk takes over with no holds barred.'' Police in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, meanwhile, said leading human rights activist and criminal lawyer <PERSON> Charita </PERSON> <PERSON> Lankapura </PERSON> was shot and killed Friday by two unidentified men. No details were released. Sinhalese radicals launched a campaign to topple the government two years ago to protest peace overtures being made to Tamil rebels demanding an independent nation in the northeast. The Sinhalese front says too many concessions are being made to the minority Tamils, who make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population. The front has been blamed for killing 3,500 people in two years, mostly government officials, governing party members and security force personnel. The government says the radicals instigated an ongoing strike by public transport workers that has been crippling the economy for four weeks.
