<HEAD>Bush Asks 8-25 Percent Pay Hike for Senior Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; edits reference to pay raise rejection in
next last graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to give some 7,200 federal executives pay increases of 8 percent to 25 percent, with even higher raises going to a selected 200 with special skills. However, the president coupled his pay-raise plan with a proposal that the officials justify their right to the higher salaries every three years to be able to keep receiving them. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal would give full 25 percent hikes to just the most senior officials, matching a salary hike he has already advocated for federal judges. More junior officials would get smaller increases, at least initially, under the plan. The president also called for a phaseout of congressional peechmaking honoraria over a two-year period and said it should be linked to a pay raise for lawmakers. But he stopped short of recommending a specific level. Presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to take the initiative on that politically touchy subject itself, but that he was ready to work with congressional leaders on a complete package. The plan would raise the pay of top federal officials, including <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members, to $ 124,400 from the present $ 99,500. It would also raise the salary of Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> from $ 115,000 to $ 143,000. But it would not affect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s $ 200,000 salary. The total pay package would cost taxpayers $ 101 million in the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1; and $ 147 million in the following fiscal year, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He said the increases would be in addition to a 3.6 percent cost-of-living increase the president is seeking for 2.2 million federal workers. The package would, for the first time, set up a special super category for federal employes with special talents, enabling them to get salaries up to the $ 124,400 top level. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said 200 individuals would qualify for these special salaries, to be determined at a later time. He suggested that nuclear scientists, physicians or others with special talents would be the type of individual considered for the special salaries. The most controversial part of the new package, however, may be the requirement that all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> undergo a re-certification process every three years to keep their higher salaries. The procedure is designed to `` assure that these people perform at a level that justifies the higher salary. We do not believe it would weaken their rights,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He said the certification would not apply to the government's 700 high-level political appointees _ like <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members and others appointed by the president and confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ because they `` can be removed at any time without appeal'' by the president. The 7,200 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and 700 appoint executives currently make $ 68,700 to $ 80,700. Their pay is tied to the $ 89,500 that members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> get, and lawmakers' rejection of a proposed 51 percent congressional pay increase in February meant no raise for them or for judges. A private commission headed by former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volker </PERSON> has recommended a 25 percent increase immediately followed by a similar amount in 1991, applying to judges, executive branch officials, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and others such as top military officers.
