<HEAD>US to Forgive Debt to 16 African Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to forgive some African debt includes 16 nations and totals about $ 1 billion, officials said Friday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s announcement Thursday will ease the debt burden starting Oct. 1 for <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. One official estimated the face value of the loans at $ 590 million to $ 600 million. The rest would be interest already due or expected to become due over the life of the loans. An additional $ 400 million will be forgiven to seven other countries if they adopt new economic policies to put themselves into better financial shape, in cooperation with the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the International Monetary fund, the officials added. But they said some of the seven, such as <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, are not likely to adopt such programs. The others are: <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>. The officials from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> spoke on condition that their names not be used. Though <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has much heavier debt than <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the burden on many <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> countries is considered heavier because their populations are much poorer and smaller. The forgiveness was announced Thursday by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at a news conference for non-American reporters and stems from last year's economic summit. The leaders of the seven major non-Communist governments, including <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, will meet in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> next week for a meeting. One State Department official said the other nations already have forgiven most of such debt owed to them, and so have some other creditors including the Nordic countries and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. One AID official explained that many of the debts to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> go back as much as 30 years. More recently aid to the poorest countries has been given in the form of grants, as it was when major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid programs began in the 1940s. `` Some of the grants have been going to pay interest on the old loans,'' the official added. Some debtor governments have not been paying for years, so that forgiving their debts will not have much practical effect for them. The loans to be forgiven were made for development projects and as economic aid to countries considered strategically important to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The officials said there would be no effect on loans given by the government's <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to encourage the sale of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial products, by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to encourage the sale of farm products or by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for weapons and training.
