<SECOND>AM-Extradition-US,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Wins Rights Court Ruling Against Extradition to USA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> STRASBOURG </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ In a landmark ruling Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> said a West German must not be extradited to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because he could face execution if he is convicted of a double murder. <PERSON> Jens </PERSON> <PERSON> Soering </PERSON>, 22, who is jailed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, is wanted for the stabbing deaths of a girlfriend's parents in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> in 1985. The British government agreed last year to his extradition. But the court in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> said if Soering is sent to <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the prospect of execution violates his rights under the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, whose charter bans `` inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment.'' `` The applicant's extradition to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would expose him to a real risk'' of treatment banned under the European human rights charter, the court ruled. The court said if Soering were sent instead to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which also has asked for his extradition, he would not face the death penalty and would not serve years on death row, which the court said also violates the charter. Court officials said the ruling broke new ground because it involved human rights abuses that had not yet occurred. `` Normally the court has the power to rule only on ... violations of human rights,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, a lawyer at the court. Rulings by the rights court, a branch of the 23-nation Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, are not binding on the 23 council nations but are rarely ignored. Soering was arrested in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on a check fraud charge in April 1986 after evading arrest in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where he is charged in the March 30, 1985, slayings of <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Haysom </PERSON> in their home in <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Haysom </PERSON>, his girlfriend at the time, is serving a 90-year sentence for her part in the killings The court did not address Soering's guilt in the deaths of the parents, opposed Soering's relationship with their daughter. <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> said <PERSON> Soering </PERSON> has admitted to participating in the killings but has given differing accounts of the circumstances. Sending Soering to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` would not involve suffering of such exceptional intensity or duration,'' said <PERSON> Rolv </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryssdal </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the court's president. The ruling noted inmates spend between six and eight years on <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s death row as their cases go through a lengthy review process. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> abolished the death penalty in 1949. If convicted in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, Soering faces a maximum prison sentence of 10 to 15 years. <PERSON> Ryssdal </PERSON> said the court's ruling against extradition also took into account Soering's state of mind and that he was 18 at the time of the killings. Psychiatrists have said he `` had lost his personal identity in a symbiotic relationship with his girlfriend _ a powerful, persuasive and disturbed young woman.'' The court ordered the British government to pay Soering's legal costs of about $ 42,720. It dismissed minor claims by Soering, including the allegation he did not get a fair hearing in British courts that considered the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> extradition request. Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who was in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> for Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech to the Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, denounced the ruling as `` indefensible.'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Updike </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, prosecutor heading the case against Soering, said the decision was `` illogical.'' `` He is guilty of the extremely brutal murder of two human beings,'' <PERSON> Updike </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> is a body of Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the oldest organization striving for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> unity. It was founded in 1949 and is separate from the 12-nation European Economic Community.
