<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian troops shelled the Christian coast Friday, and the head of a Moslem militia said he wants missiles to counter those reportedly acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces and `` aimed at my house.'' Also Friday, scattered clashes between rival Moslem militias left two people dead and four wounded, police said. The shelling _ a daily effort to keep ships from supplying the Christian enclave _ killed three people and wounded seven, police said. The casualties from the shelling raised the overall toll to 405 people killed and 1,558 wounded since March 8, when the fighting started between the Christian forces loyal to the government led by Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and Syrian troops backing a rival Moslem Cabinet. <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia, said in the Syrian capital, <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, that he wants to match a shipload of Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles as well as T-54 and T-55 tanks he said the Christians received Thursday from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. `` They're not to threaten <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> or any other country,'' he said. `` They're to be used against the Lebanese and the parties of the national coalition,'' an alliance of six Moslem parties. His vow threatened to escalate the conflict that the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> has been trying to halt. Amal had stayed out of the fighting over the past 16 weeks. Christian sources reported in April that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s main Arab foe _ delivered six Frog-7s to the Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main militia <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, which maintains 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, demanded that the missiles shipped in April be removed because they can hit <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, 40 miles from Christian positions in mountains northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has linked the issue to lifting the naval blockade. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has not confirmed that his 20,000 mainly Christian troops possess Frog-7s and his aides have been vague in answering questions about the missiles. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> made his comments after meeting with Druse Moslem chieftain <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> party militia. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> said he had told Syrian officials that the Christians' missiles were `` aimed at my house, the house of <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> and at the Syrian headquarters'' in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> `` The Syrians must help us. We are their allies. If they can not, or will not, then it is our right to seek to purchase such advanced weapons from any source,'' <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> said. He said no official request has been made to the Syrians, but that he was waiting for President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> to return from his summer residence in the coastal city of <LOCATION> Latakia </LOCATION> to make the request. Pro-Iranian militiamen of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, and fighters of the Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION>, the mainstream Shiite Moslem militia, fought scattered gunbattles in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seaside <LOCATION> Ouzai </LOCATION> district Friday. Police reported two people killed and four wounded. Police said the fighting broke out after <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militiamen tried to sell their weekly magazine in <LOCATION> Ouzai </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> stronghold. Syrian soldiers `` are trying to separate the combatants,'' said a police spokesman, who can not be named in line with standing rules. The two groups, vying for dominance of the 1.2 million Shiites who make up <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s largest single sect, battled for two days in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> early this week. Three people were killed and 11 wounded, by police count. In another development, a source at <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s headquarters said <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> intelligence agents captured 32 <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> civilians and 10 of <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s soldiers in Moslem sectors of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Thursday. The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the soldiers were released Friday. `` Efforts are under way to obtain the release of the civilians,'' he said.
