<HEAD>Prisoners Get Choice: Measles Shots or Isolation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s program to inoculate prison inmates against German measles involves a choice: be vaccinated or isolated. Prison system spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON>, who has characterized the program as `` voluntary'' for the past several days, said Friday that 12 inmates at Downstate prison have refused vaccinations and have been kept in isolation `` for about a week.'' He said the dozen inmates would probably remain isolated several more days until doctors are sure they are n't going to get measles. <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON> continued to describe the rubella inoculation program, stemming from a German measles outbreak in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rikers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> jail complex, as voluntary. `` It is voluntary,'' he said. `` There's a medical problem out there and you've got to address the medical problem. One way of addressing the medical problem is to receive the inoculation; the other way of addressing it is for us to be sure, if you're not inoculated, that you have n't been exposed.'' <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON> said the resulting quarantines were `` for medical purposes, not punitive.'' The prison system spokesman said that about 20 guards have also refused to be vaccinated. He said they are being `` counseled'' and that if they continue to refuse vaccinations they will be required to sign a waiver indicating they have been informed of the risk they face. Having signed the waiver, they will be allowed to continue to work `` because they really only present a danger to each other,'' said <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON>. The rest of the staff and all the inmates, except those who accepted isolation, will have been vaccinated. Medical isolation, according to <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON>, means prisoners are confined to quarters and ca n't participate in group activities. Meals are brought to the prisoner. <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON> said that about 5,000 inmates and prison staff have thus far been inoculated at five prisons that health officials think might be at risk because they had accepted prisoners recently from the <LOCATION> Rikers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> complex. In all, about 7,000 doses of vaccine, costing the state $ 16 per dose, have been sent to the prisons, said <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON>. The state has refused to accept inmates from the two affected sections of <LOCATION> Rikers </LOCATION> since June 29. He said the state will begin taking prisoners again from those sections over the next few weeks.
