<HEAD>Storm Ravages Chateau d'Yquem, Other High-Priced Vineyards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORDEAUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A violent storm that swept through southwestern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> caused extensive damage to grapevines that produce some of the world's finest wines, vintners said Friday. The storm, which hit Thursday night, also was blamed for two deaths. Two men in a small plane were killed when they crashed while trying to land in <LOCATION> Pau </LOCATION>, 480 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The storm knocked down power lines, flooding factories, and shredding corn and tomato crops as well as the precious grapes of the Sauternes region. Many Sauternes were damaged, and some devastated. At Chateau d'Yquem, which produces a prized sweet white desert wine, proprietor <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lur </PERSON> <PERSON> Saluces </PERSON> said half his 1989 production was wiped out. Normally, Chateau d'Yquem produces about 75,000 bottles of wine from its 250 acres of vines in production. A bottle of 1983 Chateau d'Yquem, considered a top vintage by connoisseurs, sells for $ 150 to $ 225 in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` More than 50 percent of the 1989 harvest has been wiped out, and I have to say a part of the 1990 harvest seems to be in question,'' said <LOCATION> Lur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saluces </LOCATION>, whose family has owned Chateau d'Yquem since 1786. Some other vineyards in the area lost up to 100 percent of their grapes for this year.
