<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-US     07-07 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-US,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Says Summit Unlikely to Change Economic Direction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said Friday leaders of the major industrialized nations are unlikely to shift economic direction at next week's summit in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` We should bear in mind the economies of the world are doing very, very well,'' he told reporters in a satellite broadcast from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think anybody's talking about changing the throttle settings at this particular point in time,'' he said. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the leaders of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will make their annual examination of their economies' health. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said officials probably will reiterate the statement issued last spring by finance ministers saying an excessive rise or fall in the value of the dollar would be counterproductive. He turned aside criticism that industrialized nations' spring efforts to stem the sharp rise in the dollar against other major currencies had been futile. `` I do n't subscribe to the line of thought that says that either policy coordination or intervention is a thing of the past,'' he said. `` I would only point out that markets do have from time to time volatile periods,'' he said. `` We had one this spring.'' He noted the dollar's value had come down in recent weeks and currency markets were quiet. `` I think the process is working very well,'' he said. Central banks of leading industrialized nations mounted an expensive campaign last spring to drive down the value of the dollar. They intervened heavily in the currency markets by selling dollars to try to change its value. Finance officials of the seven major industrial powers have pledged to work together to keep the dollar stable. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said there was no need to make the nations' cooperation on exchange rates more formal, as some European officials suggest. `` We do n't see any reason to change things in any material way and that would include a more rigid approach to exchange rates,'' he said. `` We think the market is doing its job, and we would feel very uneasy about tinkering with success.'' He also said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration does not expect the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy to slip into a recession but rather have a `` soft landing.'' `` Our economy has been going forward on an upward plane for the last seven years, so if that plane changes its slope a little bit ... then that is what we think is a soft landing _ growth at slower rate,'' he said. There have been growing fears of recession in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Analysts predicted the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> likely will loosen its credit policy further in an effort to drive down consumer and business interest rates. The Federal Reserve in March 1988 began a credit-tightening drive that lifted interest rates, a move designed to dampen inflationary pressures by reducing demands for borrowing. But the central bank, in a major policy shift, last month lowered a key interest rate, and analysts believe it shortly will reduce that rate again.
