<BYLINE>Solidarity Official Opposes Debate on Return of Former German Land
^By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Solidarity official on Friday opposed any suggestions <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> should give up land that was in German hands before World War II. `` Those who question existing borders damage perspectives for stability in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, leader of Solidarity's deputies in the Polish parliament. He was responding to a suggestion by West German Finance Minister <PERSON> Theodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Waigel </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> should be reunified within its 1937 borders. That would include about a third of what is now <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> spoke to reporters after talks with West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>. The West German and Polish governments are trying to reach agreement on a new financial aid package for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and on improved conditions for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s ethnic German minority. The talks are stalled over conditions for financial assistance. The impasse forced <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> to call off a visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> he had tentatively planned this month. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said he sees `` new chances for -LRB- closer -RRB- relations between Germans and Poles,'' and that problems holding up the agreement `` are only of the second order.'' Relations were cooled further by <PERSON> Waigel </PERSON>'s comment on Sunday that Germans still have a legal right to parts of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ including large sections of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> _ that once belonged to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` The German Empire did not cease with the capitulation of the German army on May 8, 1945,'' <PERSON> Waigel </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANI