<HEAD>Oil-Eating Microorganisms May Munch on Alaskan Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Friday they are optimistic that oil-eating microorganisms may soon become valuable tools in cleaning up the Exxon oil spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said preliminary findings from an experiment in which nutrients were used to enhance the growth of such organisms on small sections of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s contaminated beaches appear to show success. In some cases, the number of organisms multiplied 100-fold only a week into the experiment and even in the early stages some beaches treated with nutrients showed `` a striking disappearance of the oil from rock surfaces,'' the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said that the results were `` potentially good news'' and that if the preliminary findings hold up <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> may begin later this summer to treat large sections of beach with nutrients to enhance oil-eating microorganism growth. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Brathauer </PERSON>, assistant administrator for research and development, said it will be several weeks before some remaining questions about the experiment will be resolved. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> began using nutrients to enhance microrganism growth on six test plots along <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s contaminated <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> beaches June 8 in hopes the growth would spur oil degredation. Some degredation has been observed in untreated areas, but in many cases there are too few microorganisms to make a significant impact. But <PERSON> Brathauer </PERSON> said the nutrients acted as a fertilizer and brought about significant increases in levels of oil-eating organisms in the test areas. He said so far there have been no signs of any side effects detrimental to the environment. In addition to the rapid growth of the microorganisms in the test areas, there has been a noticeable cleaning of rock surfaces that had not been anticipated so early, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentinetti </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> official involved in the project. Rock surfaces on which the nutrients were applied became much cleaner shortly after contact similar to soap releasing dirt from an object. But the officials warned that the cleaning may have been a physical reaction and not biological. <PERSON> Valentinetti </PERSON> said in an interview that the agency hopes to learn more about the cleansing action within the next few weeks and determine whether it was a biological reaction. He said it remains uncertain whether the oil that came off the rocks actually degraded or was simply transported. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that anywhere from 700 miles to 1,200 miles of <LOCATION> Alaskan </LOCATION> coastline _ much of it shear rock and boulders _ have been contaminated by the March 24 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> spill in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. <PERSON> Valentinetti </PERSON> said use of the oil-eating microorganisms is expected to be most productive along about 100 miles of shoreline where there is sand and sediment. He said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has estimated it would cost about $ 5 million to treat 50 miles of beach with the nutrient fertilizer to enhance microorganism growth. Most areas likely would require more than one treatment, officials suggested. That cost would be only a small portion of the overall cleanup costs facing Exxon.
