 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s supreme commander in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>, said Friday that Western tracking of the pilotless MiG-23 that zoomed across <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> undetected by Soviet radar proved the allied alert system works. On another issue, <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> reacted coolly to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s offer in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, Thursday to make another unilateral cut in short-range nuclear missiles. `` The main thing threatening us is overwhelming -LRB- Soviet -RRB- conventional forces,'' <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> told a meeting of American reporters. `` I question whether or not we are in a safer world in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today than we were, say, 10 years ago.'' On the runaway plane, <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> said two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> F-15 fighters scrambled from a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> `` as a policing action'' as it crossed into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> Tuesday. They shadowed it, hoping it would reach the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, but it crashed in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, killing a man. <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> said he accepted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s explanation that it was an accident. The pilot ejected over <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> after reporting the plane was smoking. The Soviets say their radar missed the MiG-23 as it flew on for 500 miles. The incident recalled the failure of Soviet air defenses to detect a small plane flown by German amateur pilot <PERSON> Mathias </PERSON> <PERSON> Rust </PERSON>, who landed in Red Square. `` <PERSON> Mathias </PERSON> <PERSON> Rust </PERSON> is one thing _ a little tiny plane flying 