<SECOND>AM-Aviation-Security,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Toughens Policy On Security Bulletins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced a stricter policy Friday to deal with threats against aviation, including a system that requires airlines to take countermeasures and imposes fines for disclosing security alerts. A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> order, which will go into effect Monday, replaces the system of issuing security bulletins, which was criticized after the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> last December that killed 270 people. Notices of threats against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines on the flight's route were posted in at least one foreign embassy but not distributed to the general public. Under the new order, individuals or airlines that disclose information from government security alerts without <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> authorizaton will be fined _ up to $ 1,000 for individuals and $ 10,000 for airlines. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said the system for alerting airlines will now include two types of adivsories: information circulars and security directives. The information circulars will deal with general threats of hijackings, bombings or other terrorist actions, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. `` They are basically a heads-up warning and would require no particular action,'' he said. The security directives, however, would require countermeasures by an airline, such as additional baggage inspections, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. These would be in response to specific threats against an airline, an airport or an individual flight and might include such information as the threatened time and method of attack, he said. Previously, airlines were not required to take any specific actions in response to security bulletins. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, in a news release on the new order, said airlines have been responsive to actions suggested in security bulletins but making compliance mandatory will strengthen security. Since 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has issued 93 security bulletings, about one-third of them warning of specific threats. In the case of Flight 103, an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> advisory had been issued about the threat of a bomb aboard a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline flight from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> with a different plane, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> authorities said they concluded that the threat was not related to the bombing of Flight 103. Other warnings were issued about the possibility of plastic explosives concealed in a radio-cassette player. Investigators said that such a bomb caused the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> explosion, although they have not found who planted the device. Relatives of Americans killed in the Pan Am bombing have called for public advisories whenever there is a threat against aviation, saying passengers have a right to know when they are boarding an aircraft that has been threatened. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> has rejected the suggestion, saying it would disrupt aviation and compromise intelligence gathering. On Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> announced new rules requiring airlines to install units that can detect plastic explosives in checked luggage at 40 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign airports. It did not list the airports, except for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gatwick </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and said it would take two or three years before all the units are installed.
