<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Guerrillas ambushed a police patrol and started a gun battle in which seven rebels, six policemen and a civilian were killed, the government said Friday. In <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, guerrillas planted eight bombs at banks and private companies, four of which exploded, police reported. An <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement said members of <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION>, a Maoist guerrilla group, ambushed the patrol Thursday in the <LOCATION> Puno </LOCATION> region, 600 miles southeast of the capital near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Titicaca </LOCATION>. The report said one policeman was wounded in the half-hour battle, which ended when police reinforcements arrived. The civilian killed had been hitching a ride on the police vehicle when it was attacked, police said. Guerrillas of the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement were responsible for the bombs in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, the police said. Four of bombs went off simultaneously at about 10:30 p.m. Thursday at offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Peru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and the Grana y Montero construction company, a tile factory and an auto parts store. Bomb squads defused the others, which were planted near downtown banks. Construction workers went on strike Monday for higher wages, and their union held violent demostrations Wednesday and Thursday in downtown <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. Four members of the construction union were wounded and one was killed Thursday in a confrontation with police after a march. A policeman was wounded when a stick of dynamite was thrown from a crowd of workers. Police did not comment on whether the explosions were related to the strike. Shining Path began fighting nine years ago in the Andes and its insurgency has spread to other areas. The Tupac Amaru group made its appearance in 1984, and generally carries out bombings in cities. More than 15,000 people have been killed since the guerrilla war began, according to government figures.
