nel found that between 1974 and March 1989, 46 percent of the black candidates failed to complete the five-month program at the <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. The panel claims 37 percent of Hispanic candidates and 17 percent of Anglos dropped from the program during the same period. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Stinchcomb </PERSON>, director of the institute, says the current attrition rate is only 3 percent to 4 percent for all applicants and the panel's figures may reflect some problems during the 1970s. <PERSON> Stinchcomb </PERSON> said dropout rates declined after the institute revamped its firing range test and some academic exams in 1981. `` The numbers the panel is throwing out is no reflection on the current situation,'' he said.
