<HEAD>Pentagon Announces B-2 Flight Test For Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced on Friday that the long-awaited first flight tests for the B-2 stealth bomber will be held during a 15-day period beginning Sunday. The controversial plane, which is the most radical and expensive bomber ever built, has become the target of budget cutters on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. Critics in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have expressed opposition to footing the bill for planes that could cost anyhwere between $ 500 million and $ 750 million a copy before the first plane has ever gotten off the ground. The plane, described as resembling a `` flying wing'' without conventional fuselage, is designed to penetrate Soviet borders without being detected by radar. The plane has no sharp angles and relies on the use of radar-absorbing coatings on its surface. In total, the program is expected to cost taxpayers some $ 70 billion. To date, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has invested $ 22 billion into the program. In a statement issued late Friday afternoon, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said that the plane is scheduled for `` outdoor tests and the first flight'' during a 15-day period beginning July 9. The plane has been undergoing a final check at an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The plane has been built and manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. During the 15-day period, the plane is expected to be rolled out of its hangar and undergo a series of dress rehearsal tests that include turning on its engines, slow and high-speed taxi tests on the runway and then, a full flight test For its initial flight, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plans to take the plane from <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION> for an approximately 2 -LCB- hour test flight, landing at <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, about 40 miles away, said Capt. <PERSON> Tess </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman at <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>. The tests may take several days, but there can be no exact date given for the test flight, Capt. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> said. `` Only after it looks perfect, and everything looks right, will they take it up. And you never know what day that will be,'' she said. While the news media will be allowed to observe the outdoor tests, the public `` is not invited,'' the statement issue at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. The specific date and time of the tests will not be announced in advance, but the media will be informed by midmorning if no tests are scheduled for a particular day, the statement said. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> will hold a news conference following the first flight, the statement said. While the B-2 has not been operationally tested in the field yet, individual systems were tried out along the way. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says the B-2 will not be deployed before 1991.
