<HEAD>Report: Credentials of VA Physicians Not Being Checked</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 6 grafs after 4th graf pvs, The VA, with statement from
Vietnam Vets group, comment from VA; inserts 1 graf after 6th graf pvs,
The full, with background on earlier legislation.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veterans officials were unable to prove they had checked the licenses of more than half the doctors they hired from 1986 to 1988, according to a published report Friday. According to a draft of a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, officials in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> have failed to verify credentials for doctors and medical residents at the nation's 172 VA hospitals. `` By not following applicable procedures, <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> medical centers could unknowingly hire ` problem' physicians and-or be allowing physicians with sanctions against their licenses to treat veterans,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted the report as saying. The VA, declining direct comment on the report, issued a statement Friday saying: `` Secretary -LRB- <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. -RRB- <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> views <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> studies as an effective, independent management guide aiming for better quality care for veterans. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> is concurrently conducting major management studies at <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> at <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON>'s request. VA and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are partners in seeking and delivering quality care for vets.'' The Vietnam Veterans of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report and an earlier report on mortality rates at <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> hospitals show that veterans with service-connected disabilities should be allowed to seek health care from the provider of their choice. `` If the government is unable to provide acceptable health care through the veterans hospital system, then these veterans should have the right to seek medical treatment elsewhere,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stout </PERSON>, president of the 35,000-member group. <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the group is making a false comparison. `` Any attempt to connect the mortality review or the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report with the quality of care is totally inappropriate,'' she said, explaining that mortality rates fail to reflect the condition of the patients who enter a particular hospital. Hospices, for example, have reported 100 percent rates. She noted that the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` The conditions cited do not mean that the medical services provided by the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> are substandard or that <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> physicians are incompetent.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study was requested two years ago by Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, ranking minority member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> His staff said it could not release a copy of the report because it was in draft form. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said it could not release the draft report, either. The full report, with <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> comment, is due for release in August. <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON> wrote a 1985 law telling the VA to act on those problems after the American Medical Association found 87 doctors were working for the agency even though their licenses had been revoked, suspended or restricted. VA officials said they could prove they had checked the licenses of only 105 of the 207 physicians hired from 1986 to 1988, the report said. The report also said the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> had not fulfilled promises to ensure that its doctors are qualified to practice their particular specialties. A further problem was detected with medical residents who work at VA hospitals, according to the draft report. The government watchdog agency said a records check with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> found that 165 of the 16,756 residents had been charged with criminal offenses between the early 1970s and May 1987, the Post reported. Among the more serious offenses were 68 charged with drunken driving and 67 charged with drug violations, five with vandalism and five with burglary. The records did not indicate how many charges led to convictions.
