<HEAD>Chicken Giant Gives Out $10,000 Checks to Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A millionaire who handed out $ 10,000 checks on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor while legislation that interested him was pending said the checks were political contributions, not an attempt to bribe lawmakers. `` It would be difficult to make it into a bribery case,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Travis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON>, who believes it's time to change <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' loose campaign finance laws. `` In <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, it's almost impossible to bribe a public official as long as you report it. The $ 10,000 personal checks, with the payee's name left blank, were offered by <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> `` Bo'' Pilgrim, an East <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> chicken processor, to nine of the 31 senators two days before Friday's vote on a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> workers' compensation bill. Business interests have favored the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan, but senators rejected it. <PERSON> Pilgrim </PERSON> said he was concerned about the high cost of workers' compensation in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and that he would like a law that would be a `` win-win situation for all of us. `` The common practice of mine is to give large contributions to people _ preachers, educational institutions and politicians _ and $ 10,000 or $ 100,000 is a common practice with me,'' Pilgrim said. `` It's primarily just for the name identification with the politicians ... They will answer your calls and give you an appointment and listen to you describe an issue. It does not infer a bribe,'' Pilgrim said. Most lawmakers said they returned the checks _ or planned to. But Sen. O.H. `` Ike'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said he saw nothing wrong with accepting the money. Blank payee lines like those on Pilgrim's checks are common _ because many people do n't know the formal name of a politician's campaign committee, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said `` I've received campaign contributions that size before. If the principle's wrong, it do n't matter if it's a dollar or a million, right? Everybody's got a different style,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law does not limit campaign contributions, although officeholders are barred from raising money during regular legislative sessions. There is no such prohibition on special sessions, and the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has been in special session for three weeks. `` I think it's outrageous. It offends the integrity of the whole process,'' said <PERSON> Earle </PERSON>. `` It looks horrible,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>. `` When I first heard it, I thought they were joking. It's just so outrageous. The law needs to be changed,'' said <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>. `` We need more limits about when we can take money and how much.'' Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said he was introducing a bill to prohibit campaign contributions on the Capitol grounds. `` Such overt attempts to influence the way laws are made should be stopped,'' <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
