<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rake Northeast; West Bakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A storm lashed the East with powerful wind and occassionally heavy rain on Friday, toppling trees and power lines and unleashing thunderstorms from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Much of the desert <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> had readings between 100 and 109 degrees. <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> hit a record 100 degrees in the fourth consecutive day of temperatures above 100 degrees. Strong wind pushed a utility pole onto a car with four people inside at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rodman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and knocked over trees and utility lines in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Byron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Otisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Onondaga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> One-inch diameter hail fell at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tonawanda </LOCATION>. Flooding was reported near <LOCATION> Roanoke </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Savage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and in parts of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. Other strong thunderstorms developed over western portions of the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>, central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Strong wind near <LOCATION> Conway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, destroyed several mobile homes, including one that was blown onto a nearby highway. Thunderstorms were also scattered over southwestern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, where small hail was reported. Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included .57 inches at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, La.; .53 inches at <LOCATION> Waco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; .46 inches at <LOCATION> McComb </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and .13 inches at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Temperatures began warming up across much of the nation. A large, stagnant upper level high-pressure system was centered over <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and contributed to the hot weather. Afternoon readings were in the 90s from the lower <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> across the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the central and southern <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, the central and southern Rockies to interior <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Temperatures in the 90s also were common from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to along portions of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. It was the seventh day of 100-plus temperatures at <LOCATION> Scottsbluff </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, breaking the record of six days set in July 1936. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56 degrees at <LOCATION> Arcata </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to 109 degrees at Needles, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The low in the nation Friday morning was 38 degrees at <LOCATION> Truckee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms from eastern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region to the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>; scattered thunderstorms across the upper <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and the southern Plateau; showers along the coast of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state; and sunny skies over much of the remainder of the nation Highs were expected to be in the 60s or 70s along much of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>; 70s from eastern portions of the upper Great Lakes to northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; above 90 degrees from the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the Plains and <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> into interior <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>; above 100 degrees from the central high Plains across the central Rockies, central and southern Plateau to interior valleys of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>; and in the 80s for the remainder of the nation.
