<HEAD>Gorbachev, Allies Discuss Response to Western Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to RECAST; picks up 11th `Ion Diaconu...'
and SUBS 16th pvs `Gorbachev said...' to CLARIFY Bush proposal.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the other Soviet bloc leaders Friday they are free to pursue their own views of communism, but suggested his own program of economic and social reform as a guide. `` Each country and each party has its own specifics and can continue its own individual road to socialist democracy and progress,'' he said in a dinner toast after the first day of a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact summit. His host at the banquet was President <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, the most vocal critic of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. The alliance's seven members are divided over the new policies, with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on the liberal side and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> sticking to the orthodox course. Their purposes at this summit are to discuss Western arms-reduction proposals and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact's role in a new world where <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> speaks of a `` common European home'' with no threat or fear of war. In his dinner toast, the Soviet president said: `` We took new steps today toward <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> security, rapprochement and East-West dialogue.'' He also condemned unspecified `` forces'' that want military confrontation. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> renewed what he described as the Soviet bloc's `` appeal to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to give up its policy of nuclear deterrence.'' Neither he nor <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> mentioned what was decided Friday. Reporters were barred from the conference itself, but were admitted to the banquet hall in the former royal palace long enough to hear the brief dinner toasts. Soviet <ORGAN