<UNK>Court Allows Material Which Got Harper's Banned In Britain</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has lost a legal battle to stop publication of a retired intelligence agent's book after banning an American magazine that published excerpts. The House of Lords, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top court, ruled on Thursday that `` Inside Intelligence'' by <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavendish </PERSON> could be published because the government had acknowledged the book was not a threat to national security. The government barred distribution in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> of last December's issue of the American magazine <ORGANIZATION> Harper </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, which carried excerpts It was the second major defeat for Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s attempts to gag former intelligence agents. Last October, the five-judge court rejected a long and costly attempt through British and foreign courts to ban publication of `` Spy Catcher,'' the memoirs of another ex-agent, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. Two Scottish newspapers and <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, which fought the Cavendish case, hailed the judgment as a victory over what critics call excessive secretiveness by the <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> government. `` It was an overweening use of government authority,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Glasgow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. `` The government resorted to the tactics of the bully to try to intimidate the press,'' he said. The Thatcher government says it is seeking to hold ex-agents to a vow of lifelong silence. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s publisher, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> MacArthur </PERSON>, had threatened to fight the magazine case in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Cavendish </PERSON>, a 62-year-old merchant banker, said he had not given <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s permission to publish the excerpts <PERSON> Cavendish </PERSON>, an agent from 1948-53 in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s foreign intelligence operation, described spying in East bloc countries. He also claimed that <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> resigned abruptly as British <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> prime minister in 1976 because the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> had embarrassing information about him. In December 1987 <PERSON> Cavendish </PERSON>, defying government instructions not to publish the book, had 500 copies printed at this own expense and sent them to friends as Christmas cards. A Scottish legislator passed the book on to a newspaper, The Scotsman.
