<HEAD>SLAM Missile Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday that the first free-flight test of a so-called SLAM missile resulted in a direct hit last month at a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> test site. The weapon, also known as a Standoff Land Attack Missile, is a derivative of the Harpoon missile system. It is designed to be fired from aircraft carrier-based planes and hit targets on land or ships at sea. A `` standoff'' weapon can be fired from some distance away from the target so that the plane carrying the weapon is not exposed to enemy fire. The SLAM missile makes use of an infrared system that sends a video image to the plane's pilot, who can select a specific area of the target. In a statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said the June 24 test was conducted at the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Range </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The missile was fired from a A-6E attack bomber and scored a `` direct hit'' on a simulated missile communication site, the statement said. Nine additional flights are schedule for the test program, the statement said. The missile, built by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is manufactured in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, the statement said.
