<HEAD>China's Growth Rate Slows, Government Gives Mixed Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s industrial production grew much more slowly in the first half of 1989 than in 1988, according to figures released Friday, but the government seemed unsure whether that was good or not. From an economic standpoint, the news was good: <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been trying since last fall to slow what it called overheated industrial growth that was fueling inflation and shortages. But since quelling nationwide pro-democracy protests last month, the government has sought for political reasons to show that factories are operating normally and production is climbing. News media have been filled with reports of improved production nationwide. Total industrial output from January through June was $ 172.9 billion, up 10.8 percent over the same period last year, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said, quoting the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. By comparison, industrial output in the first half of 1988 grew 17.2 percent over the same period one year earlier. This year, the government set target of gradually declining growth rates, beginning with below 16 percent in the first quarter and below 13 percent in the second. The goal for the year is a 10 increase in production over 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> might well have reported that the nation overfulfilled its target for controlling too-rapid growth. Instead, it focused on industrial production's having grown `` steadily.'' Another Xinhua dispatch said <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading industrial city, topped its production quota for the first half of the year. The news agency said <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s industrial output was $ 13.9 billion up 9 percent from last year. It said the growth `` was achieved in the face of shortages of energy, funds and raw materials during the turmoil which lasted nearly two months in the city.''
