<HEAD>Crowe: US-Soviet Ties May Be Unsettled For Long Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, retiring head of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday that his historic 11-day visit to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> revealed the superpowers are entering a period of `` uneasy transition'' that `` does not ... make me feel comfortable.'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, in a speech before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, said he hopes the two military giants are moving toward a new era in the superpower relationship, but `` to conclude that we are already there would be a serious mistake.'' The 64-year-old admiral, speaking a day after President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rejected a new call from Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for talks to eliminate short-range nuclear missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, said he believes <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should avoid `` dramatic counter-responses'' to <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> initiatives `` at this point.'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> met for more than an hour with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> two weeks ago in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during his precedent-setting tour of once-secret Soviet military installations and visits with Soviet military officers. It was the first formal visit of a Joint Chiefs chairman to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and was the latest in a series of high-level visits designed to dispel distrust between the superpowers. Last July, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> hosted Marshal <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON>, then the Soviet chief of staff, on a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit. `` There is little question in my mind that real change is afoot in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said, adding that he believed that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his supporters were committed to `` fundamental reform.'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said that while there are encouraging signs that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms and promised military cutbacks may help move away from the confrontational legacy of the postwar era, the Soviet changes `` have yet to be translated into reality.'' `` Our systems remain fundamentally competitive,'' he said. The Soviets still retain the world's largest military force and have made no major changes in their space, air defense or strategic weapons, he said. The admiral lauded the Soviet military officers he met as `` disciplined, well-trained and motivated'' and found their equipment to be `` impressive and capable in the field.'' He termed political and social changes the Soviets have initiated as `` immense and risky.'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said he believed the Soviets do n't always understand the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and `` do n't appreciate why we do n't respond move-for-move'' and `` sometimes interpret this phenomenon as threatening to them.'' `` All of this does not give me a warm, fuzzy feeling, nor make me comfortable,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. `` What can be said is that we are entering a period of uneasy transition and hopefully we are moving toward a new era in the superpower relationship.'' The admiral said the Soviets are attempting to `` shed their past'' and `` do n't appreciate why our historical realtionship still weighs heavily in our decisions.'' Therefore, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> argued, the two superpowers `` may be in this unsettled state for a long period of time.'' `` My deepest concern is that our own impatience does n't force us to move too far before we understand where the world is headed,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must `` move gradually and deliberately in reasonable steps as the horizon becomes clearer _ not before,'' he added. The military chief announced on Sunday that he will retire on Sept. 30 at the end of his second two-year term as chairman.
