Note contents of 11th graf may offend some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will nominate <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, the independent federal agency that awards nearly $ 170 million in grants each year. <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON>, whose nomination requires <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation, would succeed <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodsoll </PERSON>. A graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> is an accomplished singer, avid art collector and longtime supporter of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> arts organizations. He practices law in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for eight years, serving as chairman from 1980 to 1984. He worked for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> arts advocacy group, called <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> `` a very bright, caring guy'' who `` has a real commitment to the arts.'' Interviewed by telephone in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> himself said: `` I think it would be premature for me to suggest what I might do before I'm nominated and confirmed. I certainly would say my enthusiasm for this job is unbounded.'' If confirmed for a four-year term, <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> would take charge of an agency whose grant-making procedures have been harshly criticized by several conservative members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who have accused it of supporting pornographic or blasphemous art. The controversy focuses on the endowment's financial support of a national tour of an exhibition of photographs by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON>, who died of AIDS in March, and a grant made to an artist through the Southeastern Center for Contemporary Art. The Mapplethorpe show, which includes explicit homoerotic pictures, was scheduled to open July 1 at the Corcoran Gallery of Art here but was canceled. <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON> director <PERSON> Christina </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr-Cahall </PERSON> said the gallery wanted to avoid getting embroiled in a political battle over the endowment's congressional appropriation The works of the other grant recipient, artist <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>, include a depiction of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> on a crucifix submerged in the artist's urine <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was reported to have chosen <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> over several other candidates, including <PERSON> Schuyler </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapin </PERSON>, former dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> arts school, and <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>. Hodsoll, appointed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, left the post in February after eight years to work in the White House Office of Management and Budget. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also announcedhis intention to nominate: _ <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fort </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for administration Fort is former commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and commander of the Pacific Fleet Seabees. _ <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, deputy representative of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> with the rank of ambassador He would succeed <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>.
