<HEAD>Sultan's Birthday Overshadows International Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 14th graf, `More than...' ADDING marital
status, children. Picks up 15th graf, `The royal...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is in town for it 22nd meeting and the streets are bedecked with bunting, so why do the decorations feature the number 43 instead of 22? Because the bunting is n't for the delegates; it's for the sultan, who turns 43 on July 15. The sultan, who has 37 words in his name and title, is worth $ 30 billion and takes very good care of the 241,000 people over whom he has absolute sway. He is <PERSON> Duli </PERSON> <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Maha </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulia </PERSON> <PERSON> Paduka </PERSON> <PERSON> Seri </PERSON> <PERSON> Baginda </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Di-Pertuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Negeri </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunei </PERSON> <PERSON> Awang </PERSON> <PERSON> Muda </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolkiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mu'issaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Waddaulah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibni </PERSON> <PERSON> Duli </PERSON> <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Teramat </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulia </PERSON> <PERSON> Paduka </PERSON> <PERSON> Seri </PERSON> <PERSON> Begawan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Awang </PERSON> <PERSON> Muda </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Aifuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Saifuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sa'adul </PERSON> <PERSON> Khairi </PERSON> <PERSON> Waddin </PERSON>. Most people just call him Sir <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolkiah </PERSON>. His sultanate, 2,226 square miles on the north coast of <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION>, sits on a huge pool of oil and natural gas. The Guinness Book of World Records says Sir <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> is the world's richest individual becauwe oil income and foreign currency reserves totaling almost $ 30 billion are `` effectively at his disposal.'' Fortune magazine confirmed his enormous wealth and said King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> was second with $ 18 billion. Secular, religious and military power rest with the sultan, a hereditary ruler who is head of state, prime minister, defense minister and commander of the armed forces. One of his brothers is in charge of foreign affairs and another heads the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> of this former British protectorate, which became fully independent five years ago. As well as being the richest person in the world, Sir <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> lives with his relatives in the world's biggest palace _ a complex of buildings built with 38 types of marble on a 300-acre hill near the <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. In case friends decide to stay over, it has 1,778 rooms and 257 toilets. There are 564 chandeliers, 18 elevators, 44 staircases and a banquet hall that seats 4,000. His majesty's polo ponies have air-conditioned quarters. More than 2,000 workers completed the Istana -LRB- palace -RRB- <PERSON> Nurul </PERSON> <PERSON> Imam </PERSON> for independence in 1984 and the sultan never said how much it cost. Guesses at the time started at $ 250 million, but suppliers who know what went into it _ including 22-carat gold tiles on interior arches _ say at least $ 600 million. The sultan has two wives. He was married first to Her Majesty the <PERSON> Raja </PERSON> <PERSON> Isteri </PERSON> <PERSON> Pengiran </PERSON> <PERSON> Anak </PERSON> <PERSON> Saleha </PERSON> and then to Her Royal <PERSON> Highness </PERSON> <PERSON> Pengiran </PERSON> <PERSON> Isteri </PERSON> <PERSON> Hajjah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON>. He has three sons and six daughters. <PERSON> Saleha </PERSON>, the sultan's first cousin, resides in the Nurul Imam. Mariam -LRB- born <LOCATION> Mariam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION> -RRB- keeps house in a smaller and newer palace, <LOCATION> Nurulizza </LOCATION>, 14 miles from the capital. Their marriage caused a rift between the sultan and his father, Sir <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>, because she was a commoner and part Japanese. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> occupied <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> during World War II. The sultan met Mariam when she was a hostess on the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brunei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. The royal family, in power for 29 generations, ensures continued support for autocracy by providing subsidized food, fuel, housing and free education and medical care. There is no personal income tax. Shortly after independence, Sir <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> was quoted as saying his subjects enjoyed `` a good life. Why should they want more?'' Bruneians seem content. The happiest probably are the civil servants, who make up 46 percent of the work force of 85,000. Along with standard benefits, they get free pensions and interest-free loans to buy cars and houses. Traffic jams are common in <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, which has one car for every 2.3 people. Prince <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolkiah </PERSON>, the foreign minister, told reporters covering the conference: `` The people seem to be very happy with the way we are running things. The people accept it.'' They certainly are spared worries that trouble the foreigners here assembled. There is no national debt, no trade deficit, no balance of payments problem and the budget always shows a surplus. Oil and natural gas account for 99 percent of exports. Sir <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> was attending <ORGANIZATION> Sandhurst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> when his father abdicated in 1967 and he was summoned home at age 21 to take the throne. <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> continued to run things from behind the scenes for another 15 years, however, and the polo-playing young potentate took the opportunity to build an international reputation as a playboy. <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>'s last flirtation with an elected parliament was in 1962, when it was still a British protectorate. The Parti Rakyat <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, since outlawed, won all 16 seats on the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> refused to convene the council and an uprising ensued. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> crushed the rebellion and a state of emergency declared at the time remains in force.
