<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv10   07-07 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 10,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday July 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Recession Coming _ Or Already Here?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forget for a moment, if you will, the months-old debate on Wall Street over whether the economy is headed for a recession. Consider instead the possibility that such a slump might already have begun. This is by no means a majority view, or even suspicion, among the economists of the financial world. Many economists still argue that the recent slowing of the economy will bottom out with nothing worse than a spell of sluggish growth. Once that happy news is established, they contend, the rallying cry will be `` Onward and upward!'' for both the stock market and the producing and consuming economy. Nevertheless, some observers say, if a recession is destined to occur, it would be very much in keeping with past patterns if it were to sneak in unnoticed and take a firm hold several months before its presence is officially detected. Such a sneak-attack effect can be enhanced by the much-publicized, but still easily overlooked, lag time between economic events and the reporting of data used to measure them. The statistics that lately have heightened recession worries have covered May and June, the latter stages of the second quarter of 1989. But even as investors react to them, the third quarter is well under way. The formal definition of recession, as established by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, is at least two consecutive quarters of declines in the gross national product, after adjustment for inflation. If that kind of an event were to occur in the third and fourth quarters of this year, it would n't be certified as such until early 1990. Of course, the government and private economists employ other tools to try to get a more up-to-date reading of where things are headed. One of these, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s index of leading economic indicators, dropped 1.2 percent in May for its third decline in four months _ bordering on the traditional standard that recognizes three down months in a row as a recession warning. `` We've never been much of a fan of this index as a gauge to future economic growth,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Resler </PERSON>, economist at <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` But this latest report had an ominous quality to it.'' Given the leading indicators' spotty record in the past, many private analysts have their own favorite statistical barometers. Subscribers to the doctrine known as monetarism, for instance, argue that slow or no growth in the money supply has already sounded a clear signal of trouble ahead. Others cite the `` inverted yield curve'' _ with short-term interest rates higher than long-term interest rates _ that has prevailed for much of this year as a likely portent of stormy weather. No matter how many forecasting aids are available, though, it seems evident that the `` soft landing'' vs. recession argument on Wall Street wo n't be settled until some months after the fact. All the reports since early this year showing a slowing of economic growth `` are also the way that recessions come about,'' observed <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Legg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` If continued as they're now tracking,'' <PERSON> DeVoe </PERSON> added, `` they would indicate the growing likelihood of a recession _ if the economy is not already in one.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday July 10</NOTE>
