<HEAD>Retailers Post Slightly Better Sales Gains in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales picked up slightly at the country's big chain stores last month from May's weak pace, but growth was kept in check by a general slowdown in economic activity. `` The gains were stronger than we had seen in the prior month, but across the board they were certainly not outstanding,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronning </PERSON>, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harriman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Economists monitor retail sales for clues about consumer expenditures, which account for about two-thirds of the country's economic The reports from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailers Thursday suggested that spending on big-ticket goods, like home appliances, has slowed while outlays for less expensive merchandise have n't been crimped as much by rising credit charges, reflecting interest rate hikes earlier this year. Several department stores and specialty retailers said they benefited again last month from the gradual comeback in women's clothing sales following a deep slump during the past two years <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's biggest apparel retailers, posted an 11 percent increase in sales in the five weeks ended July 1. Besides its flagship women's clothing shops, <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> owns specialty stores such as <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>'s Secret and <ORGANIZATION> Abercrombie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON>. The take at Limited's stores open at least a year, called same-store or comparable store sales, rose 12 percent in June. Retailers and analysts consider the same-store sales a more accurate reflection of a company's performance than totals that include sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports sales on this basis. Other beneficiaries of the recovery in women's apparel included <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which said total June sales rose 14.2 percent. The department store operator, which also runs Target and <PERSON> Mervyn </PERSON>'s stores, reported same-store sales were up 6.1 percent <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> attributed its sales pickup to demand for summer fashions and increased purchases of soft home furnishings like bedding and bath goods Its June sales rose 7.6 percent and same-store sales increased 5.6 percent. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wintzer </PERSON>, who follows specialty clothing merchants for the investment firm <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, said: `` The apparel retailers are making progress but they are a little bit disappointing given how bad last year's results were.'' Recent monthly sales by apparel sellers may look much better than they actually were because they are being compared with last year, which was an exceptionally bleak time for fashion merchandising. Among the leading general merchandisers, <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the country's second-largest retailer after <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said its June sales represented an improvement after a string of disappointing months. The discounter said sales at all of its stores went up 5.7 percent in June after a 2.5 percent increase in May. Sales at K marts open at least a year picked up 2.3 percent in June after falling 0.6 percent in May. Rival discounter <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, third among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailers, turned in another robust performance, reporting a 25 percent increase in total June sales and a 10 percent gain in same-store sales. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said industrywide sales were uneven during June, with the weaker figures from the non-clothing categories. A series of indexes Edelman prepared indicated most types of retailers fared better in June than in May. The weighted average of 37 merchants' sales, on a same-store basis, rose 5.3 percent in June after a 4.2 percent May gain. The <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> index of sales at 14 department stores and discounters rose 4.6 percent last month vs. 3.8 percent the month before while the measurement of apparel retailers repeated a 7.7 percent increase. The index for hard goods, including furniture, electronics and household appliances, dropped 1.8 percent in June after rising 3.4 percent in May. In reports from other major retailers Thursday: <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 2.9 percent in the five weeks ended July 1 from a year earlier. On a comparable-store basis, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' sales increased 3.6 percent May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said sales rose 6.8 percent during the five weeks and same-store sales were up 5 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Melville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 14.6 percent increase in June sales. <PERSON> Melville </PERSON> does not report same-store sales. <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its June sales increased 6.6 percent overall and 6.4 percent on a same-store basis. F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its domestic sales increased 8.2 percent in June while its same-store sales rose 3.6 percent.
