<FIRST>r f PM-BatteryRecall     07-07 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battery Recall,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duracell Recalls Specialty Lithium Camera Batteries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHEL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is recalling two models of lithium camera batteries because of an assembly defect that can cause severe overheating and in some cases damage cameras, company officials said. The batteries affected by the recall include all <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION> XL Lithium camera batteries with the model number DL123A or DL223A and labeled `` Made in <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>.'' The DL123A is a three-volt specialty battery, while the DL223A is a six-volt specialty battery. Both are used almost exclusively in 35mm automatic cameras. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said Thursday that the overheating only occurred in eight out of an estimated 8 million batteries, but that the company decided to `` take the conservative step and alert customers.'' While no injuries have resulted from the defect, in some cases a camera's battery compartment was melted, <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said. The defect, now corrected, occurred during assembly when the anotab _ the metal strip that conducts the charge from the positive terminal to the negative terminal _ became bent, <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said. Once inside the camera, the defect could cause an internal short in the battery, leading it to overheat, he said. <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said the defect had nothing to do with the company's other business The two models in question make up about 1 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION>'s current sales volume, and costs associated with the recall are to have no significant effect on <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION>, he said. <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said the batteries are used in 35mm cameras that have automatic rewind and auto-advance. He said they tend to be newer models and are rarely used in cameras more than three or four years old. <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION> is asking consumers who are using the DL123A and DL223A batteries with the `` Made in <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' label to throw away their batteries in an outdoor trash receptacle. They should then contact the company, giving their name and address, and they will receive free replacement batteries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Eds: <ORGANIZATION> Duracell </ORGANIZATION> says consumers may call the following toll-free number to replace their batteries: 1-800-832-5333.
