<HEAD>CNW to Slash Executive Jobs By 25 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will cut about a fourth of its managers to help reduce costs and pay for a pending $ 1.6 billion buyout of the company. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Foote </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the company was offering voluntary buyouts to each of its 1,000 managers to reduce the top ranks by 250. He said managers have until Monday to decide whether to accept the buyout packages, which include severance payments based on the length of employment with <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we do n't get the 25 percent voluntarily, then we'll make involuntary cuts,'' <PERSON> Foote </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` It's part of our overall effort to reduce manpower. We are accelerating that effort because of the sale of the company.'' <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> railroad, last month agreed to a $ 50-a-share offer by an investment group formed by <ORGANIZATION> Blackstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION>'s senior management. <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION> accepted the managment-led bid following a hostile tender offer from <ORGANIZATION> Japonica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment partnership. <ORGANIZATION> CNW </ORGANIZATION> has cut its total work force to 8,500 from 10,200 in 1985.
