<FIRST>r f PM-AccountingMerger Bjt   07-07 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accounting Merger, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Big Eight Firms Agree To Merge, Two More Discuss Combining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The accounting firms <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haskins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sells and <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have agreed in principle to join forces while two larger Big Eight firms confirmed that they had entered into merger negotiations. Subject to the approval of partners at <LOCATION> Deloitte </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, the combined company would have worldwide revenue exceeding $ 4 billion and employ over 65,000 people in 101 countries. It will be known as <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Touche in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the firms said in a statement Thursday. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waterhouse </ORGANIZATION> confirmed reports that they had begun talks about a possible merger of their worldwide operations. A confidentiality agreement will be in effect for the next 60 days while the proposition is being explored. An Andersen-Waterhouse merger would create the world's largest accounting firm, reaping $ 5 billion a year in worldwide revenue and $ 2.7 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> revenue. The merger wave among the Big Eight firms began weeks ago with the announcement that <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to combine their operations to create an accounting firm with worldwide revenue of $ 4.2 billion and domestic revenue of $ 2 billion. Although <PERSON> Deloitte </PERSON> and <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> are the smallest of the so-called Big Eight firms, they have posted the most rapid growth in recent years. Between 1985 and 1988, their individual worldwide revenue jumped more than 88 percent, according to <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON>'s Accounting Report, an industry publication Last year their worldwide growth averaged 26 percent, compared with an average of 22 percent for the other Big Eight firms. <PERSON> Deloitte </PERSON> and <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> noted their desire to `` serve multinational companies in today's global economy'' as a primary reason for the merger. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kangas </PERSON>, managing partner and chief executive of <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, issued a statement saying `` a strong European capability is vital to serving our clients' needs as the economic unification of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1992 approaches.'' <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> also pointed to the economic growth of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> as a need for a strengthened presence in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The combined firm will draw on the expertise of the Japanese audit firm <ORGANIZATION> Tohmatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Awoki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Sanwa </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> organization. Worldwide, the firm will be known as <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tohmatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kangas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> will serve as chief executives of the international organization and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firm, respectively. <PERSON> Kangas </PERSON> also will serve as a managing partner of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firm. Experts generally agreed that the merger makes sense, particularly because the accounting industry has become increasingly specialized. Among Deloitte's audit clients are <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON>, publisher of the Atlanta-based <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON>'s Accounting Report. <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>'s audit clients include <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, he said. <PERSON> Deloitte </PERSON> also displays its strength in the mergers and acquisitions arena. <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> said the firm is a favorite of <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the powerful <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> tapped <PERSON> Deloitte </PERSON> to perform a number of accounting-related services for its record $ 25 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> as well as other targets, including <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON>. In a joint statement, Price Waterhouse Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> Chief Executive <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinbach </PERSON> said the the firms are seeking to benefit from the globalization of world economies, accelerating technological changes and demand for new services and investments. `` These developments are creating a demand for increased worldwide professional and financial resources which to serve clients' needs,'' their statement read. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> is the second-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> accounting firm, while Price Waterhouse ranks fifth. Together the two firms would audit almost 40 percent of the Fortune 500, which could lead to <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> concerns about a competitive imbalance, <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> said. The firms did not comment on whether any employees would be let go, but observers suspect support staff will be cut. `` They will definitely have to let people go at the support level, the non-professional staffs,'' <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> said. `` And there will be some fallout at the partner level. You do n't need two partners in charge of the same little area.'' But fees are unlikely to head lower despite savings from consolidation. `` They ca n't lower the hourly rates that they're charging, so the only thing they can save on is administrative and certain overhead costs to help the bottom line,'' said one accountant at a second-tier firm who asked not to be named.
</TEXT>
