<HEAD>State Farm Announces Lawsuit Against Nevada Insurance Rollback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it will file a lawsuit challenging a <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> law that requires auto insurers to cut their rates. `` We'll probably file the complaint by the end of next week or early in the week after that,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a spokesman at the insurer's headquarters in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said Thursday the company plans to challenge the law under the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> constitutions on the grounds that the forced rollback violates the prohibition against taking property without due process The law requires insurers to cut their rates to 15 percent below the levels of July 1, 1988, on new or renewed policies, starting in October. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who signed the rollback into law Thursday, has said he's uncertain about the measure's constitutionality. But he said Nevadans who support a rate rollback deserve a chance to have the state defend their position in court. The law allows insurance companies to raise rates only if they prove to the state insurance commissioner that they would go bankrupt without an increase. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> has the fifth-highest auto insurance rates in the nation, with drivers paying average annual premiums of $ 880, according to the state Insurance Division. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has said it also planned to challenge the rollback in court. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s largest auto insurers, said the company has n't decided whether to challenge the rollback. He said a similar bankruptcy test in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s Proposition 103 insurance rollback was ruled unconstitutional by that state's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on the grounds it denied insurers a fair return on their investment `` Farmers is as concerned as anybody about containing the cost of auto insurance in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, but this is simply not a workable way to solve the problem,'' <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from Farmers' <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> headquarters. `` You ca n't roll back prices by fiat without doing something about the underlying costs.''
