erally honor each other's tickets, competitors stopped honoring Eastern tickets after it filed for bankruptcy protection. Under the new plan, effective today, travel agents will be reimbursed for ticket refunds they gave their customers. The total amount of refund money available will be based on the volume of new Eastern tickets sold by the agents. Eastern will put $ 5 million into the reimbursement fund up front. In addition, for the rest of July, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> will pay into the fund each week the total amount of agents' sales of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> tickets that exceeds $ 3.6 million, up to a maximum of $ 1.25 million a week. In August, the cap on the amount that could go into the fund each week will increase to $ 2 million. A maximum of $ 20 million could be put into the fund from ticket sales during the life of the program. The pilots union at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> blasted the agreement, calling it `` nothing short of the blackmail of travel agents who are creditors in the Eastern bankruptcy.'' In a statement, the union said the agents are, in effect, required to sell <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> tickets in order to make sure they can collect the money <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> owes them. In addition, the pilots said, the plan makes no provision for customers who purchased their Eastern tickets directly, rather than through a travel agent.
