<HEAD>Holiday Discount Fares Light Up Reservation Switchboards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Airline reservation switchboards are lighting up like fireworks this week as thousands of travelers take advantage of bargain air fares that were sparked by the midweek July 4 holiday, airline officials say. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> ignited the Independence Day fare war with its `` Spirit of'76'' ticket prices _ $ 76 one way almost anywhere the airline flies in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Rivals that matched the fare, and those that upped the ante, reported the price-slashing lit a fire under air travelers looking for bargains. The special fares are designed to drum up business during the slack midweek holiday travel period, airline officials said. `` Traditionally, when you see a holiday falling in midweek, business travelers decide not to travel that week. That is the case this week. But this is win-win situation,'' said <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman at the airline's <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters. After Continental announced its low fares Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> matched the offer the next day. Bookings at <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> on Monday broke the airline's one-day record by about 40 percent, said spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>. `` The holiday weekend was extremely strong. The public response has been beautiful,'' he said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Braniff </LOCATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> also matched the cut-rate fares Tickets for most of the special fares must be purchased by Saturday and travel must start by that day. The fares require a round-trip purchase and carry other restrictions. Most industry observers said the holiday discounts are nothing new and amounted to an excuse to advertise. But one analyst said <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION>'s program has a different intent. `` It is a typical action by an airline that is perhaps a little tight on cash,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It is an attempt to sell fares now in order to get working capital.'' The discounts are not part of a long-term trend toward lower airline fares, he said. `` The truth is, discounted fares are harder and harder to find,'' said <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON>. <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 76 fare, offered for such a short period, would n't make much of a difference in the airline's revenue figures. But <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said response to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s holiday fares was so great that the airline added several thousand additional seats for the program. `` We are selling seat inventory that might otherwise go unsold, and the American consumers get a bargain they have n't seen in years,'' he said. Following Continental's lead, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> adopted a $ 152 round-trip fare, which applies to any of the 111 markets it serves in the 48 contiguous states. The Dallas-based airline also reported its best one-day traffic period ever last Friday, when it flew 276.84 million revenue passenger miles with an 83.5 percent load factor, officials said. `` We had extremely full flights anyway'' before the fare was announced, said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s similar fares extend to all cities it serves in the 48 states, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornacker </PERSON> at the airline's <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> headquarters. `` They are selling extremely well. We are having an extremely higher period of bookings than we had last year,'' she said. As a result of existing higher demand, Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> decided not to match the other fares. `` We looked at our loads for those days and they were high,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON>. `` So we were looking at diluting revenue we already had on the books.''
