<HEAD>Time Accuses Paramount of Trying to Deceive FCC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> lawyers have charged <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> with trying to deceive the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> about how long it would take Paramount to complete its $ 12.2 billion hostile bid for Time. The media giant's attorneys, in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> mass media bureau chief <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> released to the media Thursday, accused Paramount of making false statements in applications for approval of former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> as a voting trustee to hold Time stock. Time is fighting Paramount's $ 200-a-share bid while trying to preserve a planned merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Time's lawyers charged that although <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> it expected its original $ 10.7 billion bid to expire July 5, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> executives knew before their offer was announced that it could not close for several months because it is conditioned upon obtaining regulatory approval to operate about 800 cable television systems that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> owns The offer is now scheduled to expire July 28. Paramount called the charges a delaying tactic. `` Time continues frantically to try to block our $ 200-a-share tender offer _ the only real issue in this whole matter _ by raising questions on timing,'' <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. `` Of course it might take a few months to get the approvals,'' the statement continued. `` Our process is