company said. `` Time only wants to open up for public inspection those carefully selected areas of the record they think are useful to them.'' While Time and Paramount quarreled over the trustee, the primary issue in the struggle is before <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which will decide whether Time, in agreeing to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year, in effect put itself up for sale. If the court rules that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> did in fact put itself on the block, the media giant's board must give serious consideration to the <LOCATION> Parmount </LOCATION> offer, which <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> directors rejected as financially inadequate and too conditional. A hearing is set for Tuesday. In another courtroom, this one in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, arguments were heard Thursday in a suit brought by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary that seeks an injunction to stall the Paramount bid. Paramount attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Warden </PERSON> charged <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION> sought the injunction merely to keep in place Time's management, `` which has negotiated extremely lucrative contracts for the next decade.'' But <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> denied the charge, saying, `` We're not trying to stop the tender offer.'' He said Paramount officials were interested only in Time and `` they do n't care about <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest cable company with more than 4 million customers, wants Paramount to obtain approval as a cable television franchise owner before proceeding with a takeover. The Time subsidiary said contracts for 200 of its franchises require r