<HEAD>Congressman Urges Restraint in Venezuelan Currency Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s investigation of a foreign-exchange scandal is causing some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations to re-examine their investments in the country and to withdraw top executives. Chairman <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., in a letter to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s ambassador in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said: `` At a time when economic growth is a priority, it would be a shame to see foreign corporations discouraged from investing in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> or decide to curtail their operations `` I do not wish to interfere in any way in domestic affairs or in the judicial system in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>; nor can I comment on the merits of the case,'' <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON> said in his June 13 letter to Ambassador <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Consalvi </PERSON>. `` As a friend of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, however, I do wish to bring to your attention the problems this case is causing for foreign business,'' he said. `` Some <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations have removed their top executives and are re-examining their investments in your country.'' <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON> said that he has been told by executives of major <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations that a Venezuelan judge has issued arrest warrants for several people, including <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> executives, `` on charges of fraud in obtaining preferential foreign exchange.'' `` I understand the charges involved do not permit those accused to be granted bail,'' <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON> said. `` The executives involved claim they and their corporations are innocent.'' Replying, Ambassador <PERSON> Consalvi </PERSON> said his government `` does not welcome any discouragement to the presence of foreign businesses and investment,'' and in fact welcomes them. But he said the government, operating under a system of separation of powers, respects `` the independence of the judicial system.'' He also noted that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> acted in March to abolish the multiple exchange rate system. Investigators in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> have been examining allegations that billions of dollars in illegal profits were skimmed from a now disbanded office set up to distribute <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars at favorable exchange rates for essential imports. The investigators have been quoted in published reports as saying that some $ 2.4 billion of the $ 30 billion involved may have been touched by fraud.
