<HEAD>Larger Incentives, Lower Financing Could Be On Its Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> DETROIT </LOCATION> _ Car buyers who resisted the incentives of this spring and summer may have their patience rewarded during the next few weeks. The scenario they've been waiting for _ high rebates and low interest rates _ may be on its way. The prime rate has dropped recently and there have been indications that other interest rates, including those for cars, will fall. `` I think there's no question that the direction of interest rates is downward,'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said Thursday. The incentives, which have been around since April, are likely to stay through the end of the model year this fall because they apparently have n't done the trick. Earlier this week, the eight major vehicle manufacturers with domestic plants reported their car and light truck sales for the first half of 1989 were 4.8 percent behind the sales pace during the same time last year. That could prompt automakers to add more incentives or beef up existing ones to move out 1989 models and clear dealer lots for the 1990s, which officially debut Oct. 1, analysts say. `` It's an incredibly good buying time,'' said auto analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Inc However, he added: `` The industry is going to be very hard pressed to turn the spigot on for the third quarter. You've got the greatest levels of incentives out there and they do n't seem to be generating the interest.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Meier </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, agreed. `` It's been slow and it's beginning to taper off,'' he said Thursday. Manufacturers and dealers are wrestling with high inventory levels, estimated by some to be as much as 80 days' worth of stock at the current selling rate. `` My guess is that the industry had 76 days -LRB- worth of cars -RRB- at the end of June, with the Big Three at 78 to 80 days,'' said analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It's not a disaster, but it's uncomfortably high. A year ago, you were looking at 60, 61 or 62 days.'' One way to deflate inventory is to close production, drying up the supply of cars coming into the retail sales pipeline. That, in turn, forces layoffs. A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, declining to be identified, said the union was monitoring the sales and production figures closely to be sure that any layoffs are allowed under contracts with the Big Three. Selective plant production cuts began several months ago. This week and the next kick off the traditional summer vacation and model-changeover time, as factories are prepared for the next model year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has no production scheduled during that time. On Thursday, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Automotive Reports said domestic automakers' production levels were sharply lower this week compared with the same week a year ago The trade journal said automakers scheduled the production of 71,167 cars and trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week, 42.6 percent fewer than the 124,029 vehicles they produced during the same week last year.
