<HEAD>Acne Drug Maker Loses First Jury Verdict over Side Effects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Whether or not the first jury verdict against <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s Accutane acne medicine leads to more lawsuits will probably be irrelevant to the billion-dollar drug company, analysts say. `` There is nothing that can happen to <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> as a result of this situation,'' said <PERSON> Calvert </PERSON> <PERSON> Crary </PERSON>, a litigation analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Labe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simpson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Last week, a federal jury in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> agreed with the claim by <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> that the acne medicine sent her to the hospital with bouts of disorientation, seizures and eventually comas that lasted several days. The jury awarded Ms. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, 59, $ 1 million. Even if hundreds of people began filing such lawsuits, `` It would be a matter of utterly no consequence'' to the <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, N.J.-based drug maker, said <PERSON> Crary </PERSON>. `` In a way, I suppose you could say that's what's so sick about the whole system, but that's the system,'' he said. The powerful drug, a highly effective medicine for a severe and scarring form of acne, has been linked to 73 cases of birth defects. Its potential side effects include skin dryness, vomiting, nausea, headaches and visual disturbances. A jury in <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, found that the company failed to warn Ms. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>'s doctor adequately about Accutane's potential side effects when it was prescribed in 1984. Ms. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> at the time lived in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and now lives outside <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> `` They're not emphasizing just how toxic this drug is,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION> `` We feel the verdict is wrong, that it's inappropriate,'' said company spokeswoman <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of Swiss pharmaceutical giant <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is considering an appeal, among other options, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON> would not comment on what those might be. Accutane is not a proven cause of the seizures, but the company in 1985 included warnings indicating that such seizures have been reported in Accutane users, she said. Analysts discounted the lawsuit avalanche common to the asbestos industry, the <LOCATION> Dalkon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shield </LOCATION> or even, to a lesser degree, cigarette makers, who despite last year's first jury loss face fewer product liability suits. There just are n't enough potential plaintiffs, said <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Habermas </PERSON>, a pharmaceutical analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Sanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I'm sure this will induce others to file suit and encourage those who have, but I do n't think there are that many people who have been injured by the product,'' he said. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> has yearly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of $ 1.9 billion; Accutane accounts for only about $ 45 million to $ 50 million, said Ms. <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON>. Since the prescription drug's introduction in 1982, 1.4 million to 1.5 million people are estimated to have used it, she said. Insurance covers jury awards, and even without it, future cases would be `` financially insignificant,'' <PERSON> Crary </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON> said 30 to 35 Accutane cases are pending, and a somewhat greater number have been settled, thrown out of court or won by the company.
