<HEAD>Government Opening Stock Market to Foreign Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has opened <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s stock exchange to foreign investment in a move that paves the way toward eventual foreign-owned brokerages, newspapers reports said. <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON> <PERSON> Villareal </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, labeled as `` historical'' the introduction of new investment mechanisms since the government liberalized the rules on foreign investment in May. Many sectors of the Mexican economy had been reserved exclusively for the government and Mexican investors for years. The official said that effective Thursday, foreign companies could serve as advisers and intermediaries to Mexican brokerages from overseas offices. They would also be able to invest using foreign currency, the reports said. <PERSON> Enpinoza </PERSON> was quoted as saying that opening up the stock market would allow it to operate in a more sophisticated manner. Foreigners previously have been able to invest in the Mexican stock market, but only through local brokers and only in pesos.
