<FIRST>r f PM-727Cracks     07-07 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-727 Cracks,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Looking For Cause of Crack in Older 727</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Additional inspections of older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727s may be ordered now that airlines have found cracks on four of the planes, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered inspections and any necessary repairs of the 47 oldest 727s after <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> reported it found a 20-inch crack in one of its airplanes during a routine maintenance check June 26. A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Thursday that `` tiny'' cracks have also been found on two other planes. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> found a small crack on one plane, the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> deadline for completing the inspections is July 15. It was not known how many planes had been checked so far, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. He said that checks might be required on 405 other older 727 aircraft built during the early 1960s because of manufacturing processes used at the time, the <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` We anticipate that we will do further airworthiness directives,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said two of the three <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> planes found with cracks have been repaired and are back in service and the third will be flying shortly. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s airworthiness directive, sent by telegram last Friday to 727 operators, said `` preliminary indications are that the cracking was caused by fatigue.'' <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> engineers are trying to discover why the 25-year-old <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> jet developed the 20-inch crack in a part of its fuselage that has n't been associated with high stress. The crack was in the same general area as the rupture in an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 737 that lost part of its top over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> last year, but both <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said the cracking appeared entirely different from that in the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> plane. `` This is a unique situation,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. `` This is the first time a report of cracking has been made in this area.'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> added the cracking was not typical of the type often found in older aircraft. If not corrected, the cracks in the fuselage skin could result in rapid decompression of the plane in flight, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials suspect `` hoop tension'' fatigue, caused by outward forces against the hull in pressurized flight. The different thicknesses of aircraft skin at the overlap also could be a factor, he said. The cracked segment was brought to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> laboratories in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> where engineers were trying to find why it occurred, said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>. That analysis probably will take several days, he said. The three-engine 727, which <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> built from 1962 to 1984, was the best-selling commercial jet before being surpassed by the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737. <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said 1,765 727s are still in service, including 41 of the 47 planes covered by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order. The April 28, 1988, <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident, in which a stewardess fell to her death before the flight crew could land the badly damaged plane, focused worldwide attention on aging aircraft. The 19-year-old plane was one of the most heavily used 737s, with nearly 90,000 landings. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the probable cause of the accident was the failure of <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION>'s maintenance workers to detect significant disbonding and fatigue damage along the skin of the twin-engine jet. The crack in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> 727 </LOCATION> was found where sections of skin overlap on the left-hand side of the plane, ahead of the wings and below the windows, <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order required the removal of some seats, sidewall linings and insulation to gain access to the inside of the fuselage skin, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. The inspection normally could be accomplished by several maintenance workers in an overnight check, he said. Inspections were ordered only for the 47 oldest 727s because the inner layer of aluminum skin was made thicker on later models, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to use the heavier-gauge skin was for cost-control, not because the skin was too thin.
