<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv10   07-07 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 10,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday July 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Experts Say Bond Rally Will Lose Steam During Second Half</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices rallied to a two-year high during the second quarter of the year. But economists and analysts say they are n't optimistic about the streak continuing through the rest of the year. `` Our feeling is that the bond market has overreacted,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It tends to get carried away at times. I think this was one of those times.'' The market rally began in late March and continued through most of the April-June quarter, pulling the yield on the bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond from about 9.30 percent in late March to 8.03 percent on June 30. Bond prices move in the opposite direction from yields. Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> believes there will be a correction, in which bond prices will fall more in line with actual economic conditions. She says bond traders expected the economic slowdown to be greater than she predicts it actually will be. A slower economy is good for bonds because it usually eases inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-return investments such as bonds. Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> also believes bond traders expect the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> will ease monetary policy more than she thinks it actually will. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> encourages an increase in the supply of money to stimulate the economy when it senses a downturn. More money usually translates into lower interest rates, which boost bond prices. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, believes the bond rally has a few more months of steam left, `` but the bulk of the rally is behind us.'' He predicts the bond market would remain bullish through the current quarter because of continuing signs that the economy is slowing, which eases inflation. `` I think the long bond -LRB- the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is going to challenge and for a brief period break through the 8 percent mark,'' he said last week. But by year end, he predicts, the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> will be yielding 8.50 percent. Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was slightly more bullish, predicting the long bond would yield 8.25 percent by the end of the year. Working in favor of bond prices in the next six months, experts predict, will be an easing of monetary policy by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, slower economic growth and slower growth in the rate of inflation. Working against the market could be a depreciation in the dollar, which could blunt the fall in inflation and limit incentives for foreign investors to buy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bonds, which in turn would lower demand for the securities and soften their prices. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON>, chief fixed-income strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, credits `` technical factors'' in part for this spring's Those factors, he said, were the popularity of zero-coupon <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds and long-maturity municipal bonds. As the supply of these bonds was depleted due to the demand, their prices rose, said <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON>. Zero-coupon bonds lack the interest-bearing portion of regular bonds. Demand for the zeros increased in the March-April period as reports indicated the economy was slowing, <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> said. A similar increase in demand for long-maturity municipal bonds also pushed up their price, he said. Since then, demand for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> zeros and long municipals has weakened, <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> said, while the supply of these securities has increased, eliminating this as a factor in the bond market. But <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> is more optimistic about the market's performance during the second half than <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>. He predicts the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond will yield 7.75 percent by the end of the year. As to where individual investors should put their money, <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> recommends municipal bonds with maturities of 10 years or more, as well as municipal zero-coupon bonds in this maturity range. He also suggests mortgage-backed securities. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> cautions investors who missed the bond rally `` to be disciplined and resigned to the fact that they missed.'' He believes investors should avoid jumping into the long-maturity bond market with expectations of continued price gains. Instead, he said, they should buy shorter-duration issues, which would benefit more if the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> eases monetary policy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday July 10</NOTE>
