<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in response to forecasts for cooler, wetter weather in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> next week. Some selling may also have reflected pre-weekend position-adjusting by traders reluctant to go home holding `` buy'' positions amid uncertainty about the weather. `` This is a very nervous market,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Prices rallied strongly earlier in the week on predictions of an extended heat wave in the <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Belt </LOCATION> but some forecasters have since offered more moderate outlooks. A change to cooler, wetter weather would be particularly good for the corn crop, analysts said. Wheat futures retreated in early trading on weather forecasts favorable for winter-wheat harvesting. In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 4.04 a bushel; corn was 3 \ cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at $ 2.75 -LCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to -LCB- cent lower with July at $ 1.60 a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents lower to 3 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 7.68 -LCB- a bushel Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were unchanged to .48 cent lower with August at 69.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent lower with August at 81 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .30 cent higher with July at 47.07 cents a pou