<HEAD>First Wildcat Stikers Fired In Bitter Coal Walkout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with pickets blocking hearing,
and CORRECT number of workers fired to 28 sted 29. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
`The dismissals...'. This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coal company whose contract with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> includes a no-strike clause has fired 28 wildcat strikers who refused to return to work, the first firings of the four-week wildcat walkout, officials said today. The company could n't hold a formal hearing on the firings late this morning in <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION>, because 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> members blocked a meeting hall. Representatives of <PERSON> Toney </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> refused to cross a picket line that surrounded the <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Armory. Dismissal forms given the workers said they were fired for refusing to cross pickets at <PERSON> Toney </PERSON>'s Branch's mine in <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION>. The delay in the formal hearing does not mean the firings are postponed. `` This should tell them that all it's going to do is incite the workers,'' <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> international executive board member <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION>. Earlier, officials at <PERSON> Toney </PERSON>'s Branch headquarters in <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION> refused to comment on the dismissals beyond saying the company was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Bituminous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which in February 1988 signed a <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> contract that included a no-strike clause. A coal industry manual says there are 56 employees at the <ORGANIZATION> Toney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION> mine, but does not specify how many are <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> members. The dismissals are the first during a four-week wildcat sympathy strike by <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> members backing colleagues at the <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> who have been on strike since April. <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION>, unlike most other coal companies, has no contract with the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION>, and the union has sanctioned that strike but not the wildcat walkout at other companies. As many as 46,000 miners in 10 states have stayed off the job at one time or another since the unauthorized walkouts began June 12. Today, about 37,000 miners in eight states were off their jobs. A two-week vacation period for many miners ends at midnight Sunday and several locals have discussed or plan to consider returning to work, fearing what happened to the <PERSON> Toney </PERSON>'s Branch miners. `` Some of them think if this goes down the drain, miners might be in bad shape _ they -LRB- coal companies -RRB- might bust the union,'' said <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, the president of a <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> local that represents <LOCATION> Zanesville </LOCATION>, Ohio-area miners. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said Thursday he wanted <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> to step in and help end the strikes. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> should ask <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> to settle their organizations' differences so that 1,900 striking <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> miners can return The union and the company have n't been at the bargaining table for several weeks now.
