<HEAD>Government Rests Case in Racketeering Trial; Plays `Sleaze' Tapes</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf from end to CORRECT spelling of Rabinowitz; picks
up penultimate graf pvs bg'ng, The case ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government rested its case Friday in the first securities racketeering trial after playing a tape of a former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> trader telling a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION> executive after an alleged illegal deal: `` Welcome to the world of being a sleaze.'' Also, defense lawyers declined Friday to cross-examine <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> Chief Executive <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> for fear of introducing into evidence potentially damaging information about <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 650 million plea deal with the government. The `` sleaze'' tape was one of 14 conversations played by federal prosecutors at the closely watched Wall Street fraud trial of five partners in <LOCATION> Princeton-Newport </LOCATION>, a defunct brokerage, and ex-Drexel trader <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>. The tape involves charges that <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> told <PERSON> Princeton-Newport </PERSON> to sell blocks of stock in <ORGANIZATION> C.O.M.B. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to try to drive its share price below $ 16 in 1985 before a $ 25 million <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> bond offering to the Minneapolis-based merchandiser. `` I want you to, you know, get rid of it,'' <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> partner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON> on April 11, 1985. `` I want you to get it down to at least 15 -RCB- at least, and hopefully lower.'' <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON> later that day told <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> he sold 40,000 shares of the stock through another party in an attempt to drive the price down. <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>: `` Agreed, uh, that was good. ... You're a sleaze bag.'' <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON>: `` You taught me man. ... Hey, listen turkey.'' <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>: `` Welcome to the world of being a sleaze.'' After playing the tape to the jury of nine women and three men, prosecutors rested their case. <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Grand </PERSON>, told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> that certain charges against his client should be dismissed because <ORGANIZATION> C.O.M.B. </ORGANIZATION>'s stock never fell below $ 16. Grand said disclosure of the transaction was unnecessary because the stock was traded in the over-the-counter market, which is governed by different rules than major exchanges. Other defense lawyers asked <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to throw out a bevy of mail fraud, wire fraud and racketeering charges. The judge did not immediately rule on the requests, but indicated he was uncertain about some of the government's charges. The C.O.M.B. deal also played a major role in defense lawyers' decision not to cross-examine <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, who took the stand Thursday for the first time in a Wall Street corruption case Under questioning from Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> described <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> compliance systems and practices for underwriting securities such as convertible bonds, the kind used in the C.O.M.B. transaction. Defense lawyers said Friday that cross-examining <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> in an attempt to show that the C.O.M.B. transactions were harmless could have opened the door for the government to introduce <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 650 settlement of securities law charges reached last December. The government is barred from introducing the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> deal as evidence because it is unrelated. Defense lawyers did not want to risk mentioning the deal because for fear it would have prejudiced the jury against Princeton-Newport. One of six felony counts to which <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to plead guilty involved the C.O.M.B. transaction. In addition to <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON>, on trial are <PERSON> Princeton-Newport </PERSON> partners <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>, and the firm's controller, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smotrich </PERSON>. The case overlaps the government's 98-count fraud and racketeering indictment of former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>. Much of the same evidence is expected to be introduced at <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s trial, scheduled to begin in March 1990 Princeton-Newport, a small securities firm with offices in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, went out of business after the indictment was brought last August. Neither Princeton-Newport nor <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is charged in the case.
