<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting an increased likelihood of rain in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> this weekend and late next week. Prices had opened higher on forecasts Thursday for mostly hot and dry weather in the <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Belt </LOCATION> through next week. But attitudes changed after some private meteorologists reported a weakening of the high-pressure `` ridge'' that has prevented showers and cool temperatures from reaching the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> this week. `` I think people came in this morning feeling comfortable about buying the market and expecting higher prices next week, but when the weathermen started adding precipitation, they all lost their courage,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Freed </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Weather concerns continue to dominate the grain and soybean markets, as is the rule for the growing season. `` This is a very nervous market,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. At the close of trading, wheat was -LCB- cent to 4 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 4.04 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 5 \ cents lower with July at $ 2.72 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 4 cents lower with July at $ 1.57 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 15 cents lower to 2 cents higher with July at $ 7.67 a bushel
