<HEAD>Fed Has Begun New Easing of Credit, Say Analysts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs bg'ng, Federal Reserve ... with 3 new grafs
bgng, At the ... to provide details in newly released minutes; picks up
7th graf pvs bg'ng, David Jones ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Federal Reserve, faced with further signs of a weakening economy, launched a second round of credit easing this week even before the end of a crucial midyear review of monetary policy, private economists said Friday. The analysts predicted that the move would send a variety of consumer and business interest rates lower, with one saying that a cut in commercial bank's prime lending rate could come as early as Monday. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is easing and there is clear evidence that we have passed the peak on interest rates,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <PERSON> DRI-McGraw </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, an economic consulting firm in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The development was not unexpected, although some economists were surprised that the move came even before the end of two days of meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, composed of members of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and five of the 12 regional <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> bank presidents. The committee meets eight times a year to map monetary strategy and many had expected that the central bank would begin another round of easing moves in the period following this week's meeting. At the previous meeting, held on May 16, <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy-makers decided to leave credit conditions unchanged. They noted a variety of economic statistics pointing to slower growth, according to minutes of that meeting released Friday. The `` no-change'' decision was adopted on an 11-1 vote with <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Melzer </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION>, dissenting. <PERSON> Melzer </PERSON> argued that unless the central bank eased immediately it ran the danger of increasing the possibility of a recession. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> will reveal details of this week's discussions when he delivers the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s midyear assessment of the economy in congressional testimony on July 20. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is acting because a growing number of business barometers confirm that economic growth is slowing. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday that the nation's unemployment rate climbed to 5.3 percent in June, reflecting continued declines in manufacturing and construction The uptick in the jobless rate follows other statistics showing weak auto sales, a plunge in orders for manufactured goods and lackluster retail sales. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said he expected the looser credit environment would mean that banks will cut their prime lending rate, perhaps as early as Monday. Banks dropped the prime to its current 11 percent in early June. The prime rate, traditinally considered a benchmark for business loans, now influences a variety of consumer loans, including home equity loans. Economists based their belief that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is easing credit on a slight decline in the federal funds rate, which edged down 0.25 percent to 9.25 percent in the past two days. The federal funds rate, the interest that banks charge each other to make overnight loans, is influenced by daily decisions the central bank makes on how much money to make available to the banking system. It is considered the best early-warning signal of <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> intentions to loosen or tighten credit conditions. The funds rate first dropped on Thursday to the 9.25 percent level and it held at that lower level on Friday, convincing many economists that the central bank had eased. It would mark the second move toward lower interest rates in recent weeks. The funds rate had dropped from 9.75 percent to 9.5 percent in early June. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> and the other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> have been under pressure from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration to let interest rates fall as a way of keeping the economy out of a recession. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been struggling to engineer a soft-landing where growth slows enough to dampen inflationary pressures but without a recession. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said he believed the odds were still 2-1 that the central bank would be successful in avoiding a recession this year. `` The Fed seems to be on track for a soft-landing,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. He said Friday's unemployment report was particularly encouraging because it showed that average hourly earnings, a good barometer of wage pressures, showed only a moderate increase last month.
