<SECOND>AM-Blade Battle,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilkinson Sword Barred From Showing Ultra Glide Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Friday temporarily barred <ORGANIZATION> Wilkinson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sword </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from airing television commercials for its new Ultra Glide razor. The preliminary injunction was sought by the <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which sued <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> for false advertising in May. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kimba </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> was `` likely to succeed on the merits'' of its allegations that the commercials misled the public by implying Ultra Glide's shavers were six times smoother than <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s product, Atra Plus. In the ads, Atlanta-based <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> says Ultra Glide's special lubricating strip provided a smoother shave than a similar strip on Atra Plus. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>'s ruling reversed a written opinion she made Thursday rejecting <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s request for the preliminary injunction that would bar <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> from showing the television commercials. She said she reconsidered after reviewing a market study that found no substantial differences in the smoothness of the two shaving systems. A <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> attorney, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitsky </PERSON>, asked for a stay of the order because he said its effect would be `` devastating'' to the company. The commercials are the only television advertising <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> is currently showing, he said. <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> is a small player in the $ 750 million wet-shave razor market with about a 4 percent share, compared with more than 60 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> declined to stop the injunction, which will be in effect until the case is resolved. A trial date could be set for later this summer. Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is seeking undetermined monetary damages.
