<HEAD>Dollar Falls Amid Fears of Interest Rate Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Rumors circulated... to CORRECT to ``reduce''
sted ``boost.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished lower against all major currencies except the Japanese yen Friday after a steady selloff sparked by fears that interest rates would decline. Gold prices also lost ground. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold bullion for current delivery slipped to $ 383.60 a troy ounce from $ 386.40 on Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid for gold of $ 382.00 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from Thursday's late bid of $ 384.25. Domestic currency trading began with a jolt as the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a report showing the nation's unemployment rate climbed 0.1 percent to 5.3 percent last month. Traders initially were confused by the specifics of the report, which showed lower-than-expected non-farm payroll growth coupled with a sharply higher revision for May.Non-farm businesses added just 180,000 jobs last month, but May's payroll expansion was revised upward to 207,000 jobs. `` The first reaction was the dollar went up,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrie </PERSON>, vice president and manager at <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. `` But that only lasted five minutes before the dollar came barreling off,'' he said. The report ultimately depressed the dollar by serving as yet another example of the economy's slowdown. Traders said the dollar remained under pressure from the fundamental threat it has faced throughout the week: the prospect of lower interest rates. Dollar-denominated securities like bonds are more expensive when interest rates edge lower, which depresses the need for dollars to purchase them. Rumors circulated through the market that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> may be preparing to reduce its discount rate before the weekend. `` We got a lot of -LRB- dollar -RRB- selling this afternoon,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> did not attribute the selloff solely to the unemployment report, however He stressed instead that the report `` set the stage for upcoming statistics due out next week'' by suggesting that further weakness in the economy is likely. The government is scheduled to report on industrial production, factory use and retail sales next week. Each bearish report gives the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> a greater incentive to trim interest rates. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 139.65 Japanese yen, up from 138.90 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar inched up to 139.75 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to finish at 139.20 yen, up from 138.88 yen late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6245 late Friday, more expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $ 1.6220. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> it cost $ 1.6313 to buy one pound, more expensive than $ 1.6265 late Thursday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.8705 West German marks, down from 1.8850; 1.6095 Swiss francs, down from 1.6175; 6.3505 French francs, down from 6.3935; 1,355.00 Italian lire, down from 1,365.50, and 1.1908 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1917. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.8840 West German marks, down from 1.8885; 1.6200 Swiss francs, down from 1.6210; 6.3915 French francs, down from 6.4070; 2.1272 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1310; 1,368.00 Italian lire, down from 1,370.50, and 1.1907 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1919. Traders noted that European currency markets appeared to shut down earlier than usual. Gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 385.25 a troy ounce, down from $ 386.25 on Thursday, in light trading. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, was $ 384.60, down from $ 385.00. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 383.75 bid, down from $ 384.45. Silver prices were mixed. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $ 5.209 a troy ounce from $ 5.377 on Thursday. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, silver traded at a late bid price of $ 5.37 a troy ounce, up from $ 5.36.
