<HEAD>Bond Prices Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices climbed Friday, pushed up by June employment data that provided more evidence of a slowing economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond rose about 21-32 point, or $ 6.50 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from price, declined to 8.03 from 8.09 percent late Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the nation's unemployment rate edged up to 5.3 percent in June from 5.2 percent in May as businesses created a modest 180,000 new jobs. There were signs in the report that economic growth is cooling and an indication as well of an easing of the wage inflation that has troubled some analysts. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanden </PERSON> <PERSON> Houten </PERSON>, money-market economist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the increases in non-farm payroll and hourly earnings were below market expectations. `` The consensus was about 225,000 and there was only a one-cent increase in hourly earnings,'' she said. `` The market for a long time has been focusing on signs of inflation. That definitely was positive news in terms of inflation.'' Average hourly earnings of production and supervisory workers were essentially unchanged, after rising an average 0.3 percent in the first five months of the year, the government said. The report was one of many in recent weeks that suggested the economy is easing off its brisk pace of the last several years and underscored a widely-held belief that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might now allow short-term interest rates to decline. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON>, a principal at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insight </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said despite the gains market activity was volatile in thin dealings as traders anticipated the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s next move. `` Some investors did n't know what to do with the -LRB- employment -RRB- numbers,'' <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON> said. `` The market was confused over whether the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would ease. That caused the bond market to be more volatile than usual.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has kept a tight grip on credit by encouraging higher interest rates in recent months in hopes of curbing growth and taming inflation. Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income securities such as bonds and notes. Higher interest rates also depress bond prices. Market observers noted on Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> had eased policy as indicated by a declining federal funds rate and the fact that the central bank had not drained reserves from the banking system. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, prices of short-term government issues rose between 3-16 point and 7-32 point, intermediate maturities gained between 7-32 point and \ point and 20-year issues advanced between 11-32 point and 19-32 point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 3.31 to 1,190.16. In corporate trading,