<SECOND>AM-727 Cracks,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Considering More Inspections of Older 727s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> may order inspections of more older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 jetliners as a precaution after cracks were found in the fuselages of three 727s flown by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Friday. Spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials were considering requiring inspections on approximately 400 of the three-engine jets built by The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the late 1960s. No cracks have been reported among those jets, and any inspection would be `` purely a precautionary and prudent measure by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. If not corrected, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said, the cracks could lead to sudden decompression of the aircraft cabin. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered inspections and any necessary repairs of the 47 oldest 727s after <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> found a 20-inch crack in a 25-year-old jet during a June 26 maintenance check. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said tiny cracks were found on the two other 727s after the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued its airworthiness directive June 30. All three planes have been repaired, <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> has 16 jets that required inspection, and the checks were being completed Friday night, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> said 41 of the 47 planes are still in service. Among other carriers flying them are <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, with two planes, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, with three, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, with seven, and Trump Shuttle, with one. Spokesmen for those companies said most of the planes had been inspected, with no cracks found. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> deadline for completing the inspections is July 15. <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said he had not received an official report of how many planes had been checked. The 20-inch crack was in the same general area as the break in an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 737 that lost part of its top over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> last year, but <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said the cracking appeared to be entirely different. `` This is the first time a report of cracking has been made in this area,'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said, adding that the cracking was not typical of the type often found in older aircraft. <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said Thursday <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials suspect `` hoop tension'' fatigue, caused by outward forces in pressurized flight against the different thicknesses of aircraft skin where skin sections overlap. The cracked segment was brought earlier this week to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> laboratories in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> where engineers are trying to find out why it occurred. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said Friday it probably would take about a week for the analysis to be completed. The three-engine 727, built from 1962 to 1984, was the best-selling commercial jet before being surpassed by the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> said 1,765 of the 727s are still in service.
