<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Dockworkers     07-07 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Dockworkers,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Dock Strike Set for Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s largest union on Friday called a dock strike starting Tuesday to compel employers to continue national negotiations on pay and conditions. After its dockworker members voted nearly 3-to-1 to strike, the 1.4 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> ordered out its 9,400 registered dockworkers and said the stoppage could last for months. The strike vote was 6,067 in favor and 2,111 against for an indefinite strike to protest the employers' refusal to allow national talks after the end of the National Dock Labor Scheme this week. `` Dockers must understand that if they walk out not all of them will be coming back. That's not a threat, it's economic reality,'' said <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Finney </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employers </ORGANIZATION>. `` If any registered dock worker is sacked during the course of the dispute, there can be no return to work until he is reinstated,'' countered <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, the union's general secretary. The employers, backed by the government, want a shift to local bargaining with the abolition July 3 of the dock labor plan at 60 ports that handle 70 percent of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s trade by volume and 50 percent by value. There are 102 ports handling the remainder, some employing fewer than 25 people. The dock labor plan guarantees registered dockworkers a paid job regardless of whether they have cargoes to handle. It was introduced during World War II to maintain a steady work force and was made permanent in 1947. The employers say the plan protected restrictive practices, forced the employment of 12 percent more workers than needed and was outdated by modern cargo handling, mainly gantry-swung containers replacing the docker's hook. Modern methods have cut the registered dock workforce from 65,000 in 1967 to 9,400. About 1,000 more workers are employed in the 102 non-plan ports, which handle the remainder of the country's trade. Large ports affected by the strike will include <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, Tees and <ORGANIZATION> Hartlepool </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Immingham </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Grimsby </LOCATION>, Forth, <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>. Most English Channel ferries should escape the strike because the ports of <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Felixstowe </LOCATION> are outside the plan. The major impact of the strike is expected on movement of cars, containerized manufactured goods, newsprint, timber, grain, perishable fruit, animal feed, iron ore and other minerals and chemicals. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil operators plan to switch their supply vessels from <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dundee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> to Norwegian ports. <PERSON> Finney </PERSON> said more than 1,000 dockworkers had quit before the strike, accepting up to 35,000 pounds, or about $ 56,700, in severance pay. `` Extensive plans have already been made by shippers and port customers to minimize the effect of a strike and safeguard the nation's trade,'' <PERSON> Finney </PERSON> said. The end of the dock labor plan means that dockworkers can be fired and non-union labor can be used on waterfronts; both actions formerly were illegal. The employers have been encouraging dockworkers to sign individual contracts.
</TEXT>
