<HEAD>Swine Semen Regulations Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New regulations for importing swine semen from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were announced Friday, but <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials say it is unlikely that shipments will be allowed until U.S.-China relations improve. The rules, proposed in March, went into effect Wednesday, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glosser </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. But spokesman <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Baggett </PERSON> said the actual shipment of semen `` is very unlikely because of the political situation.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have criticized <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for its recent crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the world's largest swine producer, may have valuable breeding stock that could be used by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers. The semen program, designed with that in mind, includes rules to guard against the introduction of certain diseases. For example, donor boars must originate in areas of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> certified as free of hog cholera, rinderpest, foot-and-mouth disease, brucellosis, tuberculosis and other afflictions. The semen samples also must be tested for disease.
